        "subtitle": "This lecture focuses on proton transfer, ionisation, pH, and titration logic in aqueous acid-base chemistry.",
        "contentHtml": "<h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul><li>Identify acids, bases, conjugate pairs, and proton transfer.</li><li>Relate strong and weak behaviour to extent of ionisation.</li><li>Use pH and titration curves to reason about solution composition.</li><li>Distinguish equivalence point from observed endpoint.</li></ul><h2>Lecture Flow Notes</h2><section><h3>Equivalence Point</h3><p>Acid-base chemistry is proton transfer, with water often acting as participant and solvent.</p></section><section><h3>Endpoint And Indicators</h3><p>Strong and weak describe extent of ionisation, not concentration.</p></section><section><h3>Strong Acid With Strong Base</h3><p>pH is logarithmic, so small pH changes represent large concentration changes.</p></section><section><h3>Weak Acid With Strong Base</h3><p>Titration curves are composition maps, not just shapes to memorise.</p></section><h2>Worked Example</h2><div class=\"example-card\"><strong>Reasoning from the lecture</strong><p>For HCl titrated with NaOH, the equivalence point occurs when moles of HCl equal moles of NaOH.</p></div><h2>Visual Summary</h2><div class=\"diagram\"><h3>Acid-base map</h3><div class=\"flow\"><span>Acid donates H+</span><span>Base accepts H+</span><span>Conjugate pair forms</span><span>pH tracks [H+]</span></div></div><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Bronsted acid</strong>proton donor.</div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Bronsted base</strong>proton acceptor.</div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Conjugate pair</strong>species differing by H+.</div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>pH</strong>-log10 of hydrogen ion concentration.</div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Endpoint</strong>indicator colour-change point.</div></div><h2>Transcript Corrections</h2><p>These notes correct obvious speech-to-text errors where the chemistry context is clear.</p><div class=\"table-wrap\"><table><tr><th>Transcript form</th><th>Use in notes</th></tr><tr><td>C0 sub3</td><td>CO3^2- carbonate</td></tr><tr><td>Welsh-like filler text</td><td>Whisper garble outside the chemistry thread</td></tr></table></div>"
