        "title": "Course orientation and mathematical practice",
        "subtitle": "This lecture focuses on course orientation and mathematical practice. The notes below turn the worked lecture flow into formulas, methods, examples, and checks for revision.",
        "contentHtml": "\n      <section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul>\n<li>Recognise the main mathematical object in a worked problem.</li>\n<li>Choose a method before doing algebraic manipulation.</li>\n<li>Check answers against domains, units, or graph behaviour.</li>\n<li>Write solutions in a form that explains the reasoning.</li>\n</ul></section>\n      <section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on course orientation and mathematical practice. The notes below turn the worked lecture flow into formulas, methods, examples, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Course orientation and mathematical practice</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>How to study it</strong><p>Rework the examples without looking, then compare your setup, restrictions, and final interpretation with these notes.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>What to check</strong><p>Look for domain restrictions, sign changes, units, or graph features before accepting an algebraic answer.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>How this course uses mathematics</h2>\n<p>The opening lecture is mostly orientation, but it gives the operating rule for the whole course: engineering mathematics is learned by doing equations, graphs, units, and interpretation together.</p>\n<p>The lecturer frames lectures as active problem-solving sessions. A good set of notes should therefore record not just final answers, but the reason an operation is allowed and the meaning of the result.</p>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol>\n<li>Before a tutorial, identify the type of object: number, expression, equation, graph, or unit statement.</li>\n<li>During work, keep equals signs aligned and write the operation applied to both sides.</li>\n<li>After a result, check whether it has the right type: a number, a formula, an interval, a graph feature, or a unit.</li>\n</ol></div>\n<div class=\"example-card\"><strong>Worked example pattern</strong><p>A useful habit from the first lecture is to treat worked examples as rehearsals. If an equation is being solved live, try to be one line ahead, then compare your equality-preserving step with the lecturer&apos;s.</p></div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Common mistakes</strong><ul>\n<li>Do not make lecture notes only a transcript of what was said; this course expects calculation practice.</li>\n<li>Keep administrative details separate from mathematical techniques so revision notes stay usable.</li>\n</ul></div>\n</section>\n      <section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>How this course uses mathematics</strong><p>A central technique or concept in this lecture.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated, so some mathematical expressions are phonetically garbled. The notes normalise obvious phrases such as \"sine\", \"cosine\", \"derivative\", \"log\", \"equals\", and formula structure, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>\n    "
