        "contentHtml": "\n      <section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul>\n<li>Track units through algebraic rearrangements.</li>\n<li>Recognise the main mathematical object in a worked problem.</li>\n<li>Choose a method before doing algebraic manipulation.</li>\n<li>Check answers against domains, units, or graph behaviour.</li>\n</ul></section>\n      <section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on units, dimensional reasoning, and rearranging formulas. The notes below turn the worked lecture flow into formulas, methods, examples, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Units, dimensional reasoning, and rearranging formulas</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>How to study it</strong><p>Rework the examples without looking, then compare your setup, restrictions, and final interpretation with these notes.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>What to check</strong><p>Look for domain restrictions, sign changes, units, or graph features before accepting an algebraic answer.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>Dimensional analysis as an equation check</h2>\n<p>Units behave algebraically. When a formula is physically meaningful, the units on both sides match after multiplication, division, and powers are accounted for.</p>\n<p>The lecture uses this to compute unknown units. Instead of memorising a unit for a constant, rearrange the formula so the constant is the subject, then substitute the known units.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>[force] = kg m s^(-2)<br>If F = G m1 m2 / r^2, then G = F r^2 / (m1 m2).<br>[G] = m^3 kg^(-1) s^(-2)</div>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol>\n<li>Make the target constant the subject of the formula.</li>\n<li>Replace every physical quantity by its base units.</li>\n<li>Cancel powers of kg, m, and s carefully.</li>\n<li>Check that the final unit would make the original equation balanced.</li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Making a variable the subject</h2>\n<p>Rearranging a formula is the same equality-preserving logic used to solve equations, except the answer is another formula rather than a single number.</p>\n<p>Engineering formulas often have several variables. Choose the target first and remove operations in the reverse order in which they affect that target.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>E = (1/2)mv^2 gives v = sqrt(2E/m), assuming v is a speed.<br>F = ma gives a = F/m and m = F/a.</div>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol>\n<li>Circle the desired subject.</li>\n<li>Clear fractions or denominators that trap it.</li>\n<li>Undo addition/subtraction, then multiplication/division, then powers/roots.</li>\n<li>State any physical restriction, such as taking the positive square root for a speed.</li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Newton gravitation example</h2>\n<p>Newton&apos;s law of gravitation is a clean example because the constant G is not dimensionless. The rearrangement step is mathematical; the unit substitution step is physical.</p>\n<p>The force unit newton is itself derived: N = kg m s^(-2). This prevents treating N as an unexplained symbol when reducing to base units.</p>\n<div class=\"example-card\"><strong>Worked example pattern</strong><p>From <span class=\"formula\">F = G m1 m2 / r^2</span>, isolate <span class=\"formula\">G</span> to get <span class=\"formula\">G = F r^2/(m1 m2)</span>. Then substitute <span class=\"formula\">[F] = kg m s^(-2)</span>, <span class=\"formula\">[r] = m</span>, and <span class=\"formula\">[m1] = [m2] = kg</span>. The result is <span class=\"formula\">m^3 kg^(-1) s^(-2)</span>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Common mistakes</strong><ul>\n<li>Do not leave force as N if the question asks for base SI units.</li>\n<li>Square the unit of distance when the formula contains r^2.</li>\n</ul></div>\n</section>\n      <section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Dimension</strong><p>The physical type of a quantity, such as mass, length, or time.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Unit</strong><p>A chosen scale for a dimension, such as kg, m, or s.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Dimensional consistency</strong><p>Every term in a physically meaningful equation must have matching units.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Subject of a formula</strong><p>The variable isolated on one side.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Inverse operation</strong><p>An operation used to undo another operation while preserving equality.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated, so some mathematical expressions are phonetically garbled. The notes normalise obvious phrases such as \"sine\", \"cosine\", \"derivative\", \"log\", \"equals\", and formula structure, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>\n    "
