        "subtitle": "This lecture focuses on factoring and solving equations. The notes below turn the worked lecture flow into formulas, methods, examples, and checks for revision.",
        "contentHtml": "\n      <section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul>\n<li>Solve equations through equality-preserving steps.</li>\n<li>Recognise the main mathematical object in a worked problem.</li>\n<li>Choose a method before doing algebraic manipulation.</li>\n<li>Check answers against domains, units, or graph behaviour.</li>\n</ul></section>\n      <section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on factoring and solving equations. The notes below turn the worked lecture flow into formulas, methods, examples, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Factoring and solving equations</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>How to study it</strong><p>Rework the examples without looking, then compare your setup, restrictions, and final interpretation with these notes.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>What to check</strong><p>Look for domain restrictions, sign changes, units, or graph features before accepting an algebraic answer.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>Factoring common factors</h2>\n<p>Factoring rewrites a sum as a product. That matters because products reveal zeros and make later cancellation or simplification possible.</p>\n<p>The lecture emphasises the highest common factor: remove the largest shared numerical and algebraic factor from every term, leaving a bracketed expression.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>3x^2z + 9xz = 3xz(x + 3)<br>ab + ac = a(b + c)</div>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol>\n<li>Find the greatest common numerical factor.</li>\n<li>For each variable, take the smallest power present in every term.</li>\n<li>Divide every term by the common factor to form the bracket.</li>\n<li>Multiply back mentally to check.</li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Zero product solving</h2>\n<p>Once an equation is written as a product equal to zero, each factor gives a possible solution. This is the zero product property.</p>\n<p>This method is valid only after one side is exactly zero. If the equation is a product equal to a nonzero number, setting each factor equal to that number is wrong.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>If A(x)B(x) = 0, then A(x) = 0 or B(x) = 0.<br>x(x + 3) = 0 gives x = 0 or x = -3.</div>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol>\n<li>Move all terms to one side so the other side is zero.</li>\n<li>Factor completely.</li>\n<li>Set each factor equal to zero.</li>\n<li>Solve each smaller equation.</li>\n<li>Check restrictions from the original equation.</li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Caveat: garbled logarithm language</h2>\n<p>Some early transcript lines mention logs while the audio is focused on algebraic manipulation. Treat them as forward references: logarithms return later as inverse functions of exponentials.</p>\n<p>At this stage, the reliable takeaway is structural: factor before solving and keep domain restrictions for expressions such as log(x).</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>log_b(x) is defined for x &gt; 0.<br>b^(log_b x) = x, for x &gt; 0.</div>\n</section>\n      <section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Common factor</strong><p>A factor shared by every term in an expression.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Factorisation</strong><p>Writing an expression as a product to reveal structure.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Zero product property</strong><p>If ab = 0, then a = 0 or b = 0.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Factor equation</strong><p>An equation solved by setting each factor equal to zero.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Factoring common factors</strong><p>A central technique or concept in this lecture.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Zero product solving</strong><p>A central technique or concept in this lecture.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated, so some mathematical expressions are phonetically garbled. The notes normalise obvious phrases such as \"sine\", \"cosine\", \"derivative\", \"log\", \"equals\", and formula structure, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>\n    "
