        "contentHtml": "\n      <section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul>\n<li>Solve equations through equality-preserving steps.</li>\n<li>Recognise the main mathematical object in a worked problem.</li>\n<li>Choose a method before doing algebraic manipulation.</li>\n<li>Check answers against domains, units, or graph behaviour.</li>\n</ul></section>\n      <section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on equality-preserving algebra and formula rearrangement. The notes below turn the worked lecture flow into formulas, methods, examples, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Equality-preserving algebra and formula rearrangement</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>How to study it</strong><p>Rework the examples without looking, then compare your setup, restrictions, and final interpretation with these notes.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>What to check</strong><p>Look for domain restrictions, sign changes, units, or graph features before accepting an algebraic answer.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>Equals signs under equals signs</h2>\n<p>This lecture makes a style point that is mathematically important: write equations vertically so each line follows from the one before by a legal operation.</p>\n<p>The phrase \"things do not move\" is a warning against unexplained transposition. Terms change sides only because an inverse operation was applied to both sides.</p>\n<div class=\"example-card\"><strong>Worked example pattern</strong><p>For <span class=\"formula\">4x + 2 = 9</span>, subtract 2 from both sides, then divide by 4. The reasoning is not that <span class=\"formula\">2</span> jumps across; it is that equality is preserved by the same subtraction.</p></div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Common mistakes</strong><ul>\n<li>Do not write a chain of expressions with equals signs if adjacent expressions are not actually equal.</li>\n<li>Do not drop a denominator or square root without recording the inverse operation.</li>\n</ul></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Making a variable the subject</h2>\n<p>Rearranging a formula is the same equality-preserving logic used to solve equations, except the answer is another formula rather than a single number.</p>\n<p>Engineering formulas often have several variables. Choose the target first and remove operations in the reverse order in which they affect that target.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>E = (1/2)mv^2 gives v = sqrt(2E/m), assuming v is a speed.<br>F = ma gives a = F/m and m = F/a.</div>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol>\n<li>Circle the desired subject.</li>\n<li>Clear fractions or denominators that trap it.</li>\n<li>Undo addition/subtraction, then multiplication/division, then powers/roots.</li>\n<li>State any physical restriction, such as taking the positive square root for a speed.</li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>First graphing link: formulas become shapes</h2>\n<p>A linear formula has a constant rate of change, so its graph is a straight line. Algebra tells you values; the graph shows the relationship as a whole.</p>\n<p>When a formula is rearranged into y = mx + c, the gradient m and vertical intercept c become visible.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>y = mx + c<br>gradient = rise/run<br>x-intercept: solve 0 = mx + c</div>\n<div class=\"diagram\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 360 210\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"Line with slope and intercept\"><line x1=\"40\" y1=\"170\" x2=\"330\" y2=\"170\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><line x1=\"70\" y1=\"190\" x2=\"70\" y2=\"25\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><line x1=\"60\" y1=\"145\" x2=\"280\" y2=\"55\" stroke=\"#2563eb\" stroke-width=\"3\"/><circle cx=\"70\" cy=\"141\" r=\"4\" fill=\"#0f766e\"/><text x=\"78\" y=\"139\" font-size=\"12\">y-intercept</text><path d=\"M160 104 h50 v-21\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#b45309\" stroke-width=\"2\"/><text x=\"166\" y=\"123\" font-size=\"12\">run</text><text x=\"214\" y=\"96\" font-size=\"12\">rise</text></svg></div>\n</section>\n      <section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Subject of a formula</strong><p>The variable isolated on one side.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Inverse operation</strong><p>An operation used to undo another operation while preserving equality.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Equals signs under equals signs</strong><p>A central technique or concept in this lecture.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Making a variable the subject</strong><p>A central technique or concept in this lecture.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>First graphing link: formulas become shapes</strong><p>A central technique or concept in this lecture.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated, so some mathematical expressions are phonetically garbled. The notes normalise obvious phrases such as \"sine\", \"cosine\", \"derivative\", \"log\", \"equals\", and formula structure, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>\n    "
