        "title": "Graphing linear and quadratic polynomials",
        "subtitle": "This lecture focuses on graphing linear and quadratic polynomials. The notes below turn the worked lecture flow into formulas, methods, examples, and checks for revision.",
        "contentHtml": "\n      <section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul>\n<li>Solve and sketch quadratic relationships using the method matched to the task.</li>\n<li>Recognise the main mathematical object in a worked problem.</li>\n<li>Choose a method before doing algebraic manipulation.</li>\n<li>Check answers against domains, units, or graph behaviour.</li>\n</ul></section>\n      <section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on graphing linear and quadratic polynomials. The notes below turn the worked lecture flow into formulas, methods, examples, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Graphing linear and quadratic polynomials</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>How to study it</strong><p>Rework the examples without looking, then compare your setup, restrictions, and final interpretation with these notes.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>What to check</strong><p>Look for domain restrictions, sign changes, units, or graph features before accepting an algebraic answer.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>Graphing linear polynomials</h2>\n<p>The lecture treats a sketch as a mathematical argument. A good sketch labels axes, intercepts, and gradient information so the reader can reconstruct the line.</p>\n<p>For y = 2x + 1, the y-intercept is 1 and increasing x by 1 raises y by 2. Two reliable points are enough to draw the line, but the slope explains its direction.</p>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol>\n<li>Put the line in y = mx + c form if possible.</li>\n<li>Mark the y-intercept c.</li>\n<li>Use the gradient m as rise/run to find another point.</li>\n<li>Optionally solve y = 0 to locate the x-intercept.</li>\n<li>Draw a straight line through the labelled points.</li>\n</ol></div>\n<div class=\"diagram\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 360 210\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"Line with slope and intercept\"><line x1=\"40\" y1=\"170\" x2=\"330\" y2=\"170\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><line x1=\"70\" y1=\"190\" x2=\"70\" y2=\"25\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><line x1=\"60\" y1=\"145\" x2=\"280\" y2=\"55\" stroke=\"#2563eb\" stroke-width=\"3\"/><circle cx=\"70\" cy=\"141\" r=\"4\" fill=\"#0f766e\"/><text x=\"78\" y=\"139\" font-size=\"12\">y-intercept</text><path d=\"M160 104 h50 v-21\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#b45309\" stroke-width=\"2\"/><text x=\"166\" y=\"123\" font-size=\"12\">run</text><text x=\"214\" y=\"96\" font-size=\"12\">rise</text></svg></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Quadratic graphs</h2>\n<p>A quadratic graph is a parabola. It opens upward when the x^2 coefficient is positive and downward when it is negative.</p>\n<p>Zeros of the quadratic are x-intercepts. Solving the equation f(x) = 0 and sketching the graph are therefore two views of the same information.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>y = ax^2 + bx + c<br>axis of symmetry: x = -b/(2a)<br>y-intercept: y = c</div>\n<div class=\"diagram\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 360 220\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"Parabola with vertex\"><line x1=\"35\" y1=\"175\" x2=\"330\" y2=\"175\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><line x1=\"180\" y1=\"195\" x2=\"180\" y2=\"25\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><path d=\"M70 45 Q180 195 290 45\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#7c3aed\" stroke-width=\"3\"/><circle cx=\"180\" cy=\"175\" r=\"4\" fill=\"#0f766e\"/><line x1=\"180\" y1=\"35\" x2=\"180\" y2=\"190\" stroke=\"#b45309\" stroke-dasharray=\"5 5\"/><text x=\"190\" y=\"168\" font-size=\"12\">vertex</text><text x=\"190\" y=\"52\" font-size=\"12\">axis</text></svg></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Sketching template</h2>\n<p>For both lines and quadratics, a sketch is graded for mathematically relevant features, not artistic smoothness.</p>\n<p>Use algebra to find the features, then draw a shape consistent with them.</p>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol>\n<li>Find intercepts by setting x = 0 and y = 0.</li>\n<li>Find turning points or asymptotes if they exist.</li>\n<li>Decide end behaviour from the leading term or denominator.</li>\n<li>Label axes and key coordinates.</li>\n<li>Use dashed lines for asymptotes or boundaries.</li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>\n      <section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Gradient</strong><p>The rate of change of y with respect to x.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Intercept</strong><p>Where a graph crosses an axis.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Linear polynomial</strong><p>A polynomial of degree one, graphed as a straight line.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Quadratic</strong><p>A polynomial with highest power x^2.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Parabola</strong><p>The U-shaped or inverted-U-shaped graph of a quadratic.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Zero</strong><p>An x-value where the graph crosses y = 0.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated, so some mathematical expressions are phonetically garbled. The notes normalise obvious phrases such as \"sine\", \"cosine\", \"derivative\", \"log\", \"equals\", and formula structure, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>\n    "
