        "slug": "2026-02-26_EMTH117-26S1-LecC-Foundations-of-Engineering-Mathematics",
        "date": "2026-02-26",
        "title": "Solving quadratic equations",
        "subtitle": "This lecture focuses on solving quadratic equations. The notes below turn the worked lecture flow into formulas, methods, examples, and checks for revision.",
        "contentHtml": "\n      <section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul>\n<li>Solve and sketch quadratic relationships using the method matched to the task.</li>\n<li>Solve equations through equality-preserving steps.</li>\n<li>Recognise the main mathematical object in a worked problem.</li>\n<li>Choose a method before doing algebraic manipulation.</li>\n</ul></section>\n      <section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on solving quadratic equations. The notes below turn the worked lecture flow into formulas, methods, examples, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Solving quadratic equations</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>How to study it</strong><p>Rework the examples without looking, then compare your setup, restrictions, and final interpretation with these notes.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>What to check</strong><p>Look for domain restrictions, sign changes, units, or graph features before accepting an algebraic answer.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>Quadratic solving by factorisation</h2>\n<p>A factorable quadratic turns the problem into two linear equations. The roots are visible once the expression is written as a product.</p>\n<p>The lecture example pattern is <span class=\"formula\">x^2 + 5x + 6 = (x + 2)(x + 3)</span>, so the zeros are -2 and -3.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>x^2 + 5x + 6 = 0<br>(x + 2)(x + 3) = 0<br>x = -2 or x = -3</div>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol>\n<li>Move everything to one side.</li>\n<li>Look for two numbers whose product is c and sum is b.</li>\n<li>Factor into two brackets.</li>\n<li>Apply the zero product property.</li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Completing the square</h2>\n<p>Completing the square rewrites a quadratic so that the squared part is isolated. It supports both solving and graph sketching.</p>\n<p>The idea is to create a perfect square by taking half the coefficient of x and correcting the constant term.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>x^2 + bx + c = (x + b/2)^2 + c - (b/2)^2<br>a(x - h)^2 + k has vertex (h, k).</div>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol>\n<li>Factor out a if the x^2 coefficient is not 1.</li>\n<li>Take half the x coefficient inside the bracket.</li>\n<li>Add and subtract the square of that half coefficient.</li>\n<li>Collect the outside constant.</li>\n<li>Read the vertex or solve by square roots.</li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Quadratic formula</h2>\n<p>The quadratic formula packages completing the square into a reusable result. Use it when factorisation is not obvious or when exact roots are required.</p>\n<p>The discriminant tells you how many real roots the graph has before you calculate them.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>For ax^2 + bx + c = 0, x = (-b +/- sqrt(b^2 - 4ac))/(2a).<br>Discriminant D = b^2 - 4ac.<br>D &gt; 0: two real roots; D = 0: repeated root; D &lt; 0: complex roots.</div>\n<div class=\"table-wrap\"><table><tr><th>Discriminant</th><th>Graph meaning</th><th>Solutions</th></tr><tr><td>D &gt; 0</td><td>Crosses x-axis twice</td><td>Two distinct real roots</td></tr><tr><td>D = 0</td><td>Touches x-axis at vertex</td><td>One repeated real root</td></tr><tr><td>D &lt; 0</td><td>No real x-intercepts</td><td>Complex conjugate roots</td></tr></table></div>\n</section>\n      <section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Root</strong><p>A solution of f(x) = 0.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Discriminant</strong><p>The b^2 - 4ac part of the quadratic formula, controlling root type.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Completed square form</strong><p>A(x - h)^2 + k, where the vertex is visible.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Vertex</strong><p>The turning point of a parabola.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Quadratic solving by factorisation</strong><p>A central technique or concept in this lecture.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Completing the square</strong><p>A central technique or concept in this lecture.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated, so some mathematical expressions are phonetically garbled. The notes normalise obvious phrases such as \"sine\", \"cosine\", \"derivative\", \"log\", \"equals\", and formula structure, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>\n    "
