        "contentHtml": "\n      <section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul>\n<li>Solve and sketch quadratic relationships using the method matched to the task.</li>\n<li>Recognise the main mathematical object in a worked problem.</li>\n<li>Choose a method before doing algebraic manipulation.</li>\n<li>Check answers against domains, units, or graph behaviour.</li>\n</ul></section>\n      <section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on quadratic graphs and completed square form. The notes below turn the worked lecture flow into formulas, methods, examples, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Quadratic graphs and completed square form</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>How to study it</strong><p>Rework the examples without looking, then compare your setup, restrictions, and final interpretation with these notes.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>What to check</strong><p>Look for domain restrictions, sign changes, units, or graph features before accepting an algebraic answer.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>Completed square form and vertex</h2>\n<p>The completed square form <span class=\"formula\">a(x - h)^2 + k</span> displays the vertex directly. The squared term is always nonnegative, so the sign of a determines whether the vertex is a minimum or maximum.</p>\n<p>This is why completing the square is not just a solving trick; it is a graphing tool.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>y = a(x - h)^2 + k<br>vertex = (h, k)<br>axis of symmetry: x = h</div>\n<div class=\"diagram\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 360 220\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"Parabola with vertex\"><line x1=\"35\" y1=\"175\" x2=\"330\" y2=\"175\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><line x1=\"180\" y1=\"195\" x2=\"180\" y2=\"25\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><path d=\"M70 45 Q180 195 290 45\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#7c3aed\" stroke-width=\"3\"/><circle cx=\"180\" cy=\"175\" r=\"4\" fill=\"#0f766e\"/><line x1=\"180\" y1=\"35\" x2=\"180\" y2=\"190\" stroke=\"#b45309\" stroke-dasharray=\"5 5\"/><text x=\"190\" y=\"168\" font-size=\"12\">vertex</text><text x=\"190\" y=\"52\" font-size=\"12\">axis</text></svg></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Quadratic formula</h2>\n<p>The quadratic formula packages completing the square into a reusable result. Use it when factorisation is not obvious or when exact roots are required.</p>\n<p>The discriminant tells you how many real roots the graph has before you calculate them.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>For ax^2 + bx + c = 0, x = (-b +/- sqrt(b^2 - 4ac))/(2a).<br>Discriminant D = b^2 - 4ac.<br>D &gt; 0: two real roots; D = 0: repeated root; D &lt; 0: complex roots.</div>\n<div class=\"table-wrap\"><table><tr><th>Discriminant</th><th>Graph meaning</th><th>Solutions</th></tr><tr><td>D &gt; 0</td><td>Crosses x-axis twice</td><td>Two distinct real roots</td></tr><tr><td>D = 0</td><td>Touches x-axis at vertex</td><td>One repeated real root</td></tr><tr><td>D &lt; 0</td><td>No real x-intercepts</td><td>Complex conjugate roots</td></tr></table></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Sketching template</h2>\n<p>For both lines and quadratics, a sketch is graded for mathematically relevant features, not artistic smoothness.</p>\n<p>Use algebra to find the features, then draw a shape consistent with them.</p>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol>\n<li>Find intercepts by setting x = 0 and y = 0.</li>\n<li>Find turning points or asymptotes if they exist.</li>\n<li>Decide end behaviour from the leading term or denominator.</li>\n<li>Label axes and key coordinates.</li>\n<li>Use dashed lines for asymptotes or boundaries.</li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>\n      <section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Completed square form and vertex</strong><p>A central technique or concept in this lecture.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Quadratic formula</strong><p>A central technique or concept in this lecture.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Sketching template</strong><p>A central technique or concept in this lecture.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated, so some mathematical expressions are phonetically garbled. The notes normalise obvious phrases such as \"sine\", \"cosine\", \"derivative\", \"log\", \"equals\", and formula structure, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>\n    "
