        "title": "Simultaneous equations by substitution and elimination",
        "subtitle": "This lecture focuses on simultaneous equations by substitution and elimination. The notes below turn the worked lecture flow into formulas, methods, examples, and checks for revision.",
        "contentHtml": "\n      <section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul>\n<li>Solve equations through equality-preserving steps.</li>\n<li>Recognise the main mathematical object in a worked problem.</li>\n<li>Choose a method before doing algebraic manipulation.</li>\n<li>Check answers against domains, units, or graph behaviour.</li>\n</ul></section>\n      <section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on simultaneous equations by substitution and elimination. The notes below turn the worked lecture flow into formulas, methods, examples, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Simultaneous equations by substitution and elimination</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>How to study it</strong><p>Rework the examples without looking, then compare your setup, restrictions, and final interpretation with these notes.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>What to check</strong><p>Look for domain restrictions, sign changes, units, or graph features before accepting an algebraic answer.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>Substitution in simultaneous equations</h2>\n<p>Substitution turns a two-variable system into one equation in one variable. It is most natural when one equation already gives y or x explicitly.</p>\n<p>After solving the one-variable equation, substitute back to find the paired coordinate.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>If y = 2x + 1 and y = x^2, solve x^2 = 2x + 1.<br>A solution pair (x, y) must satisfy both original equations.</div>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol>\n<li>Solve one equation for one variable.</li>\n<li>Substitute that expression into the other equation.</li>\n<li>Solve the resulting one-variable equation.</li>\n<li>Substitute each result back.</li>\n<li>Write ordered pairs and check both equations.</li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Elimination in simultaneous equations</h2>\n<p>Elimination uses addition or subtraction of equation multiples to remove a variable. It is efficient when both equations are linear.</p>\n<p>The key is that multiplying a whole equation by a nonzero constant gives an equivalent equation; adding equivalent equations preserves the common solutions.</p>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol>\n<li>Line up x, y, and constants.</li>\n<li>Choose multipliers so one variable has opposite coefficients.</li>\n<li>Add the equations to eliminate that variable.</li>\n<li>Solve for the remaining variable.</li>\n<li>Back-substitute.</li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Graphical interpretation of systems</h2>\n<p>A simultaneous solution is an intersection point. A line and parabola can intersect twice, once, or not at all in the real plane.</p>\n<p>This graph view is a useful check on algebra: if the discriminant is negative, the graphs do not meet in real coordinates.</p>\n<div class=\"diagram\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 360 220\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"Line intersecting a parabola\"><line x1=\"35\" y1=\"175\" x2=\"330\" y2=\"175\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><line x1=\"65\" y1=\"195\" x2=\"65\" y2=\"25\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><path d=\"M80 50 Q175 195 300 50\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#7c3aed\" stroke-width=\"3\"/><line x1=\"70\" y1=\"155\" x2=\"300\" y2=\"70\" stroke=\"#2563eb\" stroke-width=\"3\"/><circle cx=\"110\" cy=\"140\" r=\"4\" fill=\"#0f766e\"/><circle cx=\"247\" cy=\"90\" r=\"4\" fill=\"#0f766e\"/><text x=\"116\" y=\"134\" font-size=\"12\">solution</text><text x=\"252\" y=\"84\" font-size=\"12\">solution</text></svg></div>\n</section>\n      <section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>System</strong><p>Two or more equations considered together.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Substitution</strong><p>Replace one variable using an expression from another equation.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Elimination</strong><p>Add or subtract multiples of equations to remove a variable.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Intersection</strong><p>A point satisfying both equations, visible where graphs cross.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Substitution in simultaneous equations</strong><p>A central technique or concept in this lecture.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Elimination in simultaneous equations</strong><p>A central technique or concept in this lecture.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated, so some mathematical expressions are phonetically garbled. The notes normalise obvious phrases such as \"sine\", \"cosine\", \"derivative\", \"log\", \"equals\", and formula structure, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>\n    "
