        "subtitle": "This lecture focuses on inequalities and sign charts. The notes below turn the worked lecture flow into formulas, methods, examples, and checks for revision.",
        "contentHtml": "\n      <section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul>\n<li>Recognise the main mathematical object in a worked problem.</li>\n<li>Choose a method before doing algebraic manipulation.</li>\n<li>Check answers against domains, units, or graph behaviour.</li>\n<li>Write solutions in a form that explains the reasoning.</li>\n</ul></section>\n      <section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on inequalities and sign charts. The notes below turn the worked lecture flow into formulas, methods, examples, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Inequalities and sign charts</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>How to study it</strong><p>Rework the examples without looking, then compare your setup, restrictions, and final interpretation with these notes.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>What to check</strong><p>Look for domain restrictions, sign changes, units, or graph features before accepting an algebraic answer.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>Inequalities as regions</h2>\n<p>Solving an inequality means finding where a comparison is true. Graphs help because they turn \"less than\" and \"greater than\" into above/below relationships.</p>\n<p>Unlike equations, inequalities usually return intervals. Endpoints are included only for <= or >= and only when the expression is defined there.</p>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol>\n<li>Move the comparison into a single expression compared with zero.</li>\n<li>Find zeros and undefined points.</li>\n<li>Split the number line at those critical values.</li>\n<li>Test the sign on each interval.</li>\n<li>Use the inequality symbol to select intervals.</li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Sign chart method</h2>\n<p>A sign chart organises the interval testing needed for polynomial and rational inequalities.</p>\n<p>The only places the sign of a continuous factor can change are zeros or undefined points. Between them, a single test value is enough.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>For (x - a)(x - b) &gt; 0, check intervals (-infinity,a), (a,b), (b,infinity).</div>\n<div class=\"diagram\"><table><tr><th>Interval</th><th>(-infinity, a)</th><th>a</th><th>(a, b)</th><th>b</th><th>(b, infinity)</th></tr><tr><td>sign of f(x)</td><td>+</td><td>0</td><td>-</td><td>0</td><td>+</td></tr><tr><td>f(x) &gt; 0?</td><td>yes</td><td>depends on strictness</td><td>no</td><td>depends on strictness</td><td>yes</td></tr></table></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Rational inequalities and asymptotes</h2>\n<p>For a rational expression, denominator zeros are not solutions even if they appear on a sign chart. They mark breaks in the graph and must be excluded.</p>\n<p>The transcript uses graph language such as approaching a horizontal level and shooting up near zero. That is asymptotic behaviour, not an ordinary intercept.</p>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Common mistakes</strong><ul>\n<li>Do not multiply an inequality by a variable expression without knowing its sign; the inequality direction may flip.</li>\n<li>Never include a point where the original denominator is zero.</li>\n</ul></div>\n</section>\n      <section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Inequality</strong><p>A comparison using &lt;, &lt;=, &gt;, or &gt;=.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Solution interval</strong><p>A range of values rather than a single value.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Critical number</strong><p>A zero or undefined value where sign can change.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Test interval</strong><p>An interval checked to decide whether an inequality is true.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Inequalities as regions</strong><p>A central technique or concept in this lecture.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Sign chart method</strong><p>A central technique or concept in this lecture.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated, so some mathematical expressions are phonetically garbled. The notes normalise obvious phrases such as \"sine\", \"cosine\", \"derivative\", \"log\", \"equals\", and formula structure, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>\n    "
