        "subtitle": "This lecture focuses on absolute value as distance. The notes below turn the worked lecture flow into formulas, methods, examples, and checks for revision.",
        "contentHtml": "\n      <section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul>\n<li>Solve equations through equality-preserving steps.</li>\n<li>Recognise the main mathematical object in a worked problem.</li>\n<li>Choose a method before doing algebraic manipulation.</li>\n<li>Check answers against domains, units, or graph behaviour.</li>\n</ul></section>\n      <section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on absolute value as distance. The notes below turn the worked lecture flow into formulas, methods, examples, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Absolute value as distance</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>How to study it</strong><p>Rework the examples without looking, then compare your setup, restrictions, and final interpretation with these notes.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>What to check</strong><p>Look for domain restrictions, sign changes, units, or graph features before accepting an algebraic answer.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>Absolute value means distance</h2>\n<p>Absolute value is best read geometrically: |x - a| is the distance from x to a on the number line.</p>\n<p>This explains why equations such as |x - 2| = 6 usually have two solutions: one point lies six units to the right and one six units to the left.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>|x - a| = d means x = a + d or x = a - d, for d &gt;= 0.<br>|x| = x if x &gt;= 0, and |x| = -x if x &lt; 0.</div>\n<div class=\"diagram\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 380 120\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"Absolute value distance on number line\"><line x1=\"35\" y1=\"70\" x2=\"345\" y2=\"70\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><line x1=\"130\" y1=\"60\" x2=\"130\" y2=\"80\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><line x1=\"250\" y1=\"60\" x2=\"250\" y2=\"80\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><line x1=\"190\" y1=\"55\" x2=\"190\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"#0f766e\" stroke-width=\"2\"/><path d=\"M190 45 C170 25 145 25 130 45\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#2563eb\"/><path d=\"M190 45 C210 25 235 25 250 45\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#2563eb\"/><text x=\"185\" y=\"103\" font-size=\"12\">a</text><text x=\"118\" y=\"103\" font-size=\"12\">a-d</text><text x=\"238\" y=\"103\" font-size=\"12\">a+d</text><text x=\"155\" y=\"25\" font-size=\"12\">distance d</text></svg></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Solving absolute value equations</h2>\n<p>When removing absolute value signs, split into cases rather than treating the bars like brackets.</p>\n<p>The plus-or-minus appears because the same distance can come from either side of the centre.</p>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol>\n<li>Isolate the absolute value term.</li>\n<li>Check that the right-hand side is nonnegative.</li>\n<li>Split into inside = positive value and inside = negative value.</li>\n<li>Solve both equations.</li>\n<li>Check candidates in the original equation.</li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Absolute value inequalities</h2>\n<p>The direction of an absolute value inequality determines whether the answer is between two endpoints or outside them.</p>\n<p>For distance less than d, stay inside the interval. For distance greater than d, go outside the interval.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>|x - a| &lt; d means a - d &lt; x &lt; a + d.<br>|x - a| &gt; d means x &lt; a - d or x &gt; a + d.</div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Common mistakes</strong><ul>\n<li>Do not write one interval for a &quot;greater than&quot; distance statement; it usually splits into two rays.</li>\n</ul></div>\n</section>\n      <section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Absolute value</strong><p>Distance from zero on the number line.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Distance equation</strong><p>An equation that can split into left and right cases.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Absolute value means distance</strong><p>A central technique or concept in this lecture.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Solving absolute value equations</strong><p>A central technique or concept in this lecture.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Absolute value inequalities</strong><p>A central technique or concept in this lecture.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated, so some mathematical expressions are phonetically garbled. The notes normalise obvious phrases such as \"sine\", \"cosine\", \"derivative\", \"log\", \"equals\", and formula structure, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>\n    "
