        "title": "Complex numbers and the role of i",
        "subtitle": "This lecture focuses on complex numbers and the role of i. The notes below turn the worked lecture flow into formulas, methods, examples, and checks for revision.",
        "contentHtml": "\n      <section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul>\n<li>Compute with complex numbers in rectangular and graphical forms.</li>\n<li>Recognise the main mathematical object in a worked problem.</li>\n<li>Choose a method before doing algebraic manipulation.</li>\n<li>Check answers against domains, units, or graph behaviour.</li>\n</ul></section>\n      <section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on complex numbers and the role of i. The notes below turn the worked lecture flow into formulas, methods, examples, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Complex numbers and the role of i</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>How to study it</strong><p>Rework the examples without looking, then compare your setup, restrictions, and final interpretation with these notes.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>What to check</strong><p>Look for domain restrictions, sign changes, units, or graph features before accepting an algebraic answer.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>Introducing complex numbers</h2>\n<p>Complex numbers extend the real numbers by introducing i, defined so that i^2 = -1. This makes equations such as x^2 + 1 = 0 solvable.</p>\n<p>A complex number has a real part and an imaginary part. Keep these parts separate when adding or subtracting.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>i^2 = -1<br>a + bi: real part a, imaginary part b<br>(a + bi) + (c + di) = (a + c) + (b + d)i</div>\n<div class=\"diagram\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 320 240\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"Argand diagram\"><line x1=\"35\" y1=\"170\" x2=\"295\" y2=\"170\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><line x1=\"120\" y1=\"215\" x2=\"120\" y2=\"35\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><path d=\"M120 170 L230 85\" stroke=\"#7c3aed\" stroke-width=\"3\"/><circle cx=\"230\" cy=\"85\" r=\"5\" fill=\"#0f766e\"/><line x1=\"230\" y1=\"85\" x2=\"230\" y2=\"170\" stroke=\"#b45309\" stroke-dasharray=\"4 4\"/><line x1=\"120\" y1=\"85\" x2=\"230\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"#b45309\" stroke-dasharray=\"4 4\"/><text x=\"235\" y=\"85\" font-size=\"12\">a + bi</text><text x=\"270\" y=\"186\" font-size=\"12\">real</text><text x=\"128\" y=\"48\" font-size=\"12\">imaginary</text></svg></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Complex arithmetic</h2>\n<p>Addition and subtraction combine like parts. Multiplication uses ordinary expansion, followed by replacing i^2 with -1.</p>\n<p>This is the main place errors occur: i is not a variable whose square remains i^2 after simplification.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>(a + bi)(c + di) = (ac - bd) + (ad + bc)i<br>(2 + 3i) + (-1 + 5i) = 1 + 8i<br>(2i + 3i^2) = -3 + 2i</div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Common mistakes</strong><ul>\n<li>Do not add real and imaginary parts together.</li>\n<li>Always simplify i^2 to -1.</li>\n</ul></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Argand diagrams</h2>\n<p>An Argand diagram plots a + bi as the point (a, b). The horizontal axis is real and the vertical axis is imaginary.</p>\n<p>This makes complex numbers behave like two-dimensional vectors for addition and like polar coordinates when modulus and argument are introduced.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>modulus r = sqrt(a^2 + b^2)<br>argument theta = angle from positive real axis<br>polar/exponential form: z = r e^(i theta)</div>\n<div class=\"diagram\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 320 240\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"Argand diagram\"><line x1=\"35\" y1=\"170\" x2=\"295\" y2=\"170\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><line x1=\"120\" y1=\"215\" x2=\"120\" y2=\"35\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><path d=\"M120 170 L230 85\" stroke=\"#7c3aed\" stroke-width=\"3\"/><circle cx=\"230\" cy=\"85\" r=\"5\" fill=\"#0f766e\"/><line x1=\"230\" y1=\"85\" x2=\"230\" y2=\"170\" stroke=\"#b45309\" stroke-dasharray=\"4 4\"/><line x1=\"120\" y1=\"85\" x2=\"230\" y2=\"85\" stroke=\"#b45309\" stroke-dasharray=\"4 4\"/><text x=\"235\" y=\"85\" font-size=\"12\">a + bi</text><text x=\"270\" y=\"186\" font-size=\"12\">real</text><text x=\"128\" y=\"48\" font-size=\"12\">imaginary</text></svg></div>\n</section>\n      <section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Imaginary unit</strong><p>i is defined by i^2 = -1.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Complex number</strong><p>A number a + bi with real part a and imaginary part b.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Real part</strong><p>The a in a + bi.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Imaginary part</strong><p>The b in a + bi.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Rectangular form</strong><p>The a + bi form of a complex number.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Argand diagram</strong><p>A plane with real axis horizontal and imaginary axis vertical.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Modulus</strong><p>Distance of a complex number from the origin.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Argument</strong><p>Angle made with the positive real axis.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated, so some mathematical expressions are phonetically garbled. The notes normalise obvious phrases such as \"sine\", \"cosine\", \"derivative\", \"log\", \"equals\", and formula structure, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>\n    "
