        "title": "Complex division and trigonometry begins",
        "subtitle": "This lecture focuses on complex division and trigonometry begins. The notes below turn the worked lecture flow into formulas, methods, examples, and checks for revision.",
        "contentHtml": "\n      <section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul>\n<li>Translate between triangle, unit-circle, and graph views of trigonometric expressions.</li>\n<li>Compute with complex numbers in rectangular and graphical forms.</li>\n<li>Recognise the main mathematical object in a worked problem.</li>\n<li>Choose a method before doing algebraic manipulation.</li>\n</ul></section>\n      <section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on complex division and trigonometry begins. The notes below turn the worked lecture flow into formulas, methods, examples, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Complex division and trigonometry begins</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>How to study it</strong><p>Rework the examples without looking, then compare your setup, restrictions, and final interpretation with these notes.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>What to check</strong><p>Look for domain restrictions, sign changes, units, or graph features before accepting an algebraic answer.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>Complex conjugates</h2>\n<p>The conjugate of a + bi is a - bi. Multiplying a complex number by its conjugate removes the imaginary part from the product.</p>\n<p>This is the complex-number version of rationalising a denominator.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>conj(a + bi) = a - bi<br>(a + bi)(a - bi) = a^2 + b^2</div>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol>\n<li>Change the sign of the imaginary part.</li>\n<li>Multiply numerator and denominator by the conjugate if dividing.</li>\n<li>Simplify i^2 to -1.</li>\n<li>Leave the result in a + bi form.</li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Dividing complex numbers</h2>\n<p>Division is handled by making the denominator real. Multiply top and bottom by the conjugate of the denominator.</p>\n<p>The denominator becomes a sum of squares, which is a real number.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>(a + bi)/(c + di) * (c - di)/(c - di)<br>denominator = c^2 + d^2</div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Common mistakes</strong><ul>\n<li>Use the conjugate of the denominator, not the numerator.</li>\n<li>Multiply every term in the numerator by the conjugate.</li>\n</ul></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Right-triangle trigonometric ratios</h2>\n<p>Trigonometric ratios come from comparing side lengths in right triangles. Similar triangles guarantee the ratios depend on the angle, not on the triangle size.</p>\n<p>The three core ratios are remembered by SOH-CAH-TOA.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>sin(theta) = opposite/hypotenuse<br>cos(theta) = adjacent/hypotenuse<br>tan(theta) = opposite/adjacent</div>\n<div class=\"diagram\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 340 210\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"Right triangle trig ratios\"><path d=\"M60 160 L280 160 L280 45 Z\" fill=\"#eef6ff\" stroke=\"#2563eb\" stroke-width=\"3\"/><path d=\"M260 160 v-20 h20\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><text x=\"155\" y=\"180\" font-size=\"12\">adjacent</text><text x=\"288\" y=\"105\" font-size=\"12\">opposite</text><text x=\"150\" y=\"90\" font-size=\"12\">hypotenuse</text><path d=\"M92 160 A32 32 0 0 1 105 135\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#b45309\" stroke-width=\"2\"/><text x=\"105\" y=\"150\" font-size=\"12\">theta</text></svg></div>\n</section>\n      <section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Conjugate</strong><p>For a + bi, the conjugate is a - bi.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Modulus squared</strong><p>z times conjugate(z) = a^2 + b^2.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Sine</strong><p>Opposite divided by hypotenuse.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Cosine</strong><p>Adjacent divided by hypotenuse.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Tangent</strong><p>Opposite divided by adjacent.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated, so some mathematical expressions are phonetically garbled. The notes normalise obvious phrases such as \"sine\", \"cosine\", \"derivative\", \"log\", \"equals\", and formula structure, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>\n    "
