        "contentHtml": "\n      <section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul>\n<li>Translate between triangle, unit-circle, and graph views of trigonometric expressions.</li>\n<li>Recognise the main mathematical object in a worked problem.</li>\n<li>Choose a method before doing algebraic manipulation.</li>\n<li>Check answers against domains, units, or graph behaviour.</li>\n</ul></section>\n      <section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on trigonometry from similar triangles. The notes below turn the worked lecture flow into formulas, methods, examples, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Trigonometry from similar triangles</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>How to study it</strong><p>Rework the examples without looking, then compare your setup, restrictions, and final interpretation with these notes.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>What to check</strong><p>Look for domain restrictions, sign changes, units, or graph features before accepting an algebraic answer.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>Similar triangles and scale</h2>\n<p>If two triangles have the same angles, their corresponding sides are proportional. That is the reason a ratio such as opposite/hypotenuse can define a function of the angle.</p>\n<p>The scale factor changes lengths, but it does not change ratios of corresponding lengths.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>a/a_prime = b/b_prime = c/c_prime = scale factor<br>opposite/hypotenuse is constant for a fixed angle</div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>SOH-CAH-TOA method</h2>\n<p>Choose the ratio from the sides involved, not from habit. Mark the angle first, then label opposite, adjacent, and hypotenuse relative to that angle.</p>\n<p>Once the correct ratio is written, the remaining work is equation rearrangement.</p>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol>\n<li>Mark the given angle.</li>\n<li>Label O, A, and H relative to that angle.</li>\n<li>Choose sin, cos, or tan using the known and unknown sides.</li>\n<li>Write the ratio equation.</li>\n<li>Rearrange and calculate with the correct angle mode.</li>\n</ol></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Exact and calculator values</h2>\n<p>Some angles are handled exactly using special triangles; others are evaluated with a calculator.</p>\n<p>In either case the setup is the same. The exact value or decimal approximation comes only after the ratio equation is correct.</p>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Common mistakes</strong><ul>\n<li>Check whether the angle is in degrees or radians before pressing calculator buttons.</li>\n<li>Do not round too early in a multi-step engineering calculation.</li>\n</ul></div>\n</section>\n      <section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Similar triangles</strong><p>Triangles with equal angles and proportional side lengths.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Scale factor</strong><p>The multiplier relating corresponding sides.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Similar triangles and scale</strong><p>A central technique or concept in this lecture.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>SOH-CAH-TOA method</strong><p>A central technique or concept in this lecture.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Exact and calculator values</strong><p>A central technique or concept in this lecture.</p></div></div></section>\n      <section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated, so some mathematical expressions are phonetically garbled. The notes normalise obvious phrases such as \"sine\", \"cosine\", \"derivative\", \"log\", \"equals\", and formula structure, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>\n    "
