        "contentHtml": "<section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul><li>translate between diagrams, unit-circle facts, and trig equations.</li><li>Set up the mathematical model before calculating.</li><li>Track restrictions, units, signs, or intervals.</li><li>Write answers in context rather than as unexplained algebra.</li></ul></section><section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on trigonometric ratios in applications. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Trigonometric ratios in applications</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Revision move</strong><p>Redo the method cards on paper and compare your setup, restrictions, and interpretation.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Answer checks</strong><p>Check domains, signs, units, intervals, and graph behaviour before accepting a result.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Trig ratios in physical diagrams</h2>\n<p>The lecture uses right-triangle ratios in practical setups such as sloped wires and forces. The mathematical job is to turn the physical picture into a triangle whose sides have clear meanings.</p>\n<p>Mark the angle first. Opposite and adjacent are always relative to that angle, so relabelling after choosing a different angle is a common source of wrong equations.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>sin(theta)=opposite/hypotenuse<br>cos(theta)=adjacent/hypotenuse<br>tan(theta)=opposite/adjacent</div>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol><li>Draw the right triangle from the physical situation.</li><li>Mark known angles and sides or forces.</li><li>Choose the trig ratio that contains the known quantity and unknown quantity.</li><li>Rearrange algebraically before rounding.</li><li>Attach the physical unit in the final answer.</li></ol></div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Common mistakes</strong><ul><li>Do not choose sine/cosine/tangent from memory before labelling the sides.</li><li>If the quantity is a force, keep newtons in the interpretation, not just a bare number.</li></ul></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Reciprocal trig functions</h2>\n<p>Cosecant, secant, and cotangent are just reciprocals. They can shorten an answer, but rewriting them as fractions is usually clearer while learning.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>csc(theta)=1/sin(theta)<br>sec(theta)=1/cos(theta)<br>cot(theta)=1/tan(theta)</div>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol><li>Rewrite the reciprocal name as a fraction.</li><li>Use the original sine/cosine/tangent ratio.</li><li>Only convert back to csc/sec/cot if the question asks for it.</li></ol></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Calculator angle mode</h2>\n<p>The transcript examples use degree angles in places. Later calculus formulas for trig derivatives assume radians, so the notes must keep the angle mode visible.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>180 degrees = pi radians<br>360 degrees = 2pi radians</div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Common mistakes</strong><ul><li>A calculator in radian mode will give the wrong decimal for a degree question.</li><li>Derivative rules such as d/dx sin x = cos x are radian-based.</li></ul></div>\n</section><section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Trig ratios in physical diagrams</strong><p>The lecture uses right-triangle ratios in practical setups such as sloped wires and forces. The mathematical job is to turn the physical picture into a triangle whose sid</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Reciprocal trig functions</strong><p>Cosecant, secant, and cotangent are just reciprocals. They can shorten an answer, but rewriting them as fractions is usually clearer while learning.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Calculator angle mode</strong><p>The transcript examples use degree angles in places. Later calculus formulas for trig derivatives assume radians, so the notes must keep the angle mode visible.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated. These notes normalise obvious garbled mathematical phrases, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>"
