        "subtitle": "This lecture focuses on unit circle definitions of sine and cosine. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.",
        "contentHtml": "<section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul><li>Set up the mathematical model before calculating.</li><li>Track restrictions, units, signs, or intervals.</li><li>Write answers in context rather than as unexplained algebra.</li></ul></section><section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on unit circle definitions of sine and cosine. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Unit circle definitions of sine and cosine</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Revision move</strong><p>Redo the method cards on paper and compare your setup, restrictions, and interpretation.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Answer checks</strong><p>Check domains, signs, units, intervals, and graph behaviour before accepting a result.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Unit circle definition</h2>\n<p>The unit circle moves sine and cosine beyond acute right triangles. At angle theta, the point on the circle x^2+y^2=1 has coordinates (cos theta, sin theta).</p>\n<p>Quadrant signs now come from coordinates: x controls cosine and y controls sine.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>x^2+y^2=1<br>point at angle theta = (cos theta, sin theta)</div>\n<div class=\"diagram\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 260 260\"><circle cx=\"130\" cy=\"130\" r=\"82\" fill=\"#fff\" stroke=\"#7c3aed\" stroke-width=\"3\"/><line x1=\"25\" y1=\"130\" x2=\"235\" y2=\"130\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><line x1=\"130\" y1=\"235\" x2=\"130\" y2=\"25\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><path d=\"M130 130 L195 80\" stroke=\"#2563eb\" stroke-width=\"3\"/><circle cx=\"195\" cy=\"80\" r=\"5\" fill=\"#0f766e\"/><text x=\"150\" y=\"70\" font-size=\"12\">(cos theta, sin theta)</text></svg></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Pythagorean identity</h2>\n<p>Substituting x=cos(theta) and y=sin(theta) into the unit-circle equation gives the identity used throughout trigonometry. It is a geometric fact written as algebra.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>cos^2(theta)+sin^2(theta)=1<br>sin^2(theta)=1-cos^2(theta)</div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Radians</h2>\n<p>Radians measure angle by arc length on the unit circle. Angles written with pi, such as pi/3 or 4pi/3, are radian angles.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>pi radians = 180 degrees<br>2pi radians = one full turn</div>\n</section><section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Unit circle definition</strong><p>The unit circle moves sine and cosine beyond acute right triangles. At angle theta, the point on the circle x^2+y^2=1 has coordinates (cos theta, sin theta).</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Pythagorean identity</strong><p>Substituting x=cos(theta) and y=sin(theta) into the unit-circle equation gives the identity used throughout trigonometry. It is a geometric fact written as algebra.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Radians</strong><p>Radians measure angle by arc length on the unit circle. Angles written with pi, such as pi/3 or 4pi/3, are radian angles.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated. These notes normalise obvious garbled mathematical phrases, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>"
