        "contentHtml": "<section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul><li>translate between diagrams, unit-circle facts, and trig equations.</li><li>Set up the mathematical model before calculating.</li><li>Track restrictions, units, signs, or intervals.</li><li>Write answers in context rather than as unexplained algebra.</li></ul></section><section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on solving transformed trig equations. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Solving transformed trig equations</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Revision move</strong><p>Redo the method cards on paper and compare your setup, restrictions, and interpretation.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Answer checks</strong><p>Check domains, signs, units, intervals, and graph behaviour before accepting a result.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Solving trig equations</h2>\n<p>Trig equations often require graph or unit-circle reasoning rather than a single inverse-button answer. After isolating the trig function, find every angle in the requested interval.</p>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol><li>Undo shifts and stretches until sin, cos, or tan is isolated.</li><li>Find reference-angle solutions.</li><li>Use quadrant signs or a graph to locate all solutions.</li><li>Account for inside multipliers such as 2t.</li><li>Check the required interval.</li></ol></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Reading transformations</h2>\n<p>The constants around a trig function describe visible graph changes. Outside constants change height and midline; inside constants change horizontal scale and shift.</p>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol><li>Isolate the midline D.</li><li>Read the amplitude |A|.</li><li>Compute period from B.</li><li>Locate phase shift C if present.</li><li>Sketch one period and repeat.</li></ol></div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Common mistakes</strong><ul><li>Do not confuse vertical stretch A with frequency B.</li><li>Undo transformations before solving equations.</li></ul></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Tangent and asymptotes</h2>\n<p>Tangent is sin/cos, so it is undefined where cosine is zero. Its graph has vertical asymptotes at those inputs.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>tan x = sin x/cos x<br>vertical asymptotes: x=pi/2+k*pi</div>\n</section><section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Solving trig equations</strong><p>Trig equations often require graph or unit-circle reasoning rather than a single inverse-button answer. After isolating the trig function, find every angle in the request</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Reading transformations</strong><p>The constants around a trig function describe visible graph changes. Outside constants change height and midline; inside constants change horizontal scale and shift.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Tangent and asymptotes</strong><p>Tangent is sin/cos, so it is undefined where cosine is zero. Its graph has vertical asymptotes at those inputs.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated. These notes normalise obvious garbled mathematical phrases, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>"
