        "contentHtml": "<section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul><li>identify inputs, outputs, domains, and composition structure.</li><li>Set up the mathematical model before calculating.</li><li>Track restrictions, units, signs, or intervals.</li><li>Write answers in context rather than as unexplained algebra.</li></ul></section><section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on functions, domains, and ranges. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Functions, domains, and ranges</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Revision move</strong><p>Redo the method cards on paper and compare your setup, restrictions, and interpretation.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Answer checks</strong><p>Check domains, signs, units, intervals, and graph behaviour before accepting a result.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Function as input-output rule</h2>\n<p>A function assigns each allowed input exactly one output. The lecture uses this as the first major abstraction of the course, collecting polynomials, trig functions, exponentials, and logarithms under one language.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>f: domain -&gt; codomain<br>x maps to f(x)</div>\n<div class=\"diagram\"><div class=\"flow\"><span>input x</span><span>function f</span><span>output f(x)</span></div></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Domain and range</h2>\n<p>The domain is the set of inputs a function accepts. The range is the set of outputs it actually produces. Restrictions come from denominators, square roots, and logarithms.</p>\n<div class=\"table-wrap\"><table><tr><th>Operation</th><th>Restriction</th></tr><tr><td>1/g(x)</td><td>g(x) not equal 0</td></tr><tr><td>sqrt(g(x))</td><td>g(x) &gt;= 0</td></tr><tr><td>log(g(x))</td><td>g(x) &gt; 0</td></tr></table></div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Common mistakes</strong><ul><li>Do not include an input that makes a denominator zero.</li><li>Range is not automatically the same as codomain.</li></ul></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Function notation</h2>\n<p>f(x) means the output of f at input x. It is not multiplication. This notation lets you evaluate, combine, and compose functions precisely.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>If f(x)=x^2, then f(3)=9<br>If g(x)=sin x, then g(pi/4)=sqrt(2)/2</div>\n</section><section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Function as input-output rule</strong><p>A function assigns each allowed input exactly one output. The lecture uses this as the first major abstraction of the course, collecting polynomials, trig functions, expo</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Domain and range</strong><p>The domain is the set of inputs a function accepts. The range is the set of outputs it actually produces. Restrictions come from denominators, square roots, and logarithm</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Function notation</strong><p>f(x) means the output of f at input x. It is not multiplication. This notation lets you evaluate, combine, and compose functions precisely.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated. These notes normalise obvious garbled mathematical phrases, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>"
