        "contentHtml": "<section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul><li>identify inputs, outputs, domains, and composition structure.</li><li>Set up the mathematical model before calculating.</li><li>Track restrictions, units, signs, or intervals.</li><li>Write answers in context rather than as unexplained algebra.</li></ul></section><section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on combining and composing functions. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Combining and composing functions</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Revision move</strong><p>Redo the method cards on paper and compare your setup, restrictions, and interpretation.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Answer checks</strong><p>Check domains, signs, units, intervals, and graph behaviour before accepting a result.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Arithmetic of functions</h2>\n<p>Functions can be added, subtracted, multiplied, and divided pointwise. Feed in the input first, combine the outputs second.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>(f+g)(x)=f(x)+g(x)<br>(fg)(x)=f(x)g(x)<br>(f/g)(x)=f(x)/g(x), with g(x) not equal 0</div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Composition</h2>\n<p>Composition feeds the output of one function into another. This is the same inside/outside structure that later becomes the chain rule.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>(f o g)(x)=f(g(x))<br>If f(u)=sin u and g(x)=x^2, then f(g(x))=sin(x^2)</div>\n<div class=\"diagram\"><div class=\"flow\"><span>x</span><span>g(x)</span><span>f(g(x))</span></div></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Domain of a composite</h2>\n<p>For f(g(x)) to be defined, x must be allowed in g and g(x) must be allowed in f. This two-stage check is vital with logs and roots.</p>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol><li>Check the inner function is defined.</li><li>Apply the outer domain restriction to the inner output.</li><li>Intersect all restrictions.</li></ol></div>\n</section><section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Arithmetic of functions</strong><p>Functions can be added, subtracted, multiplied, and divided pointwise. Feed in the input first, combine the outputs second.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Composition</strong><p>Composition feeds the output of one function into another. This is the same inside/outside structure that later becomes the chain rule.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Domain of a composite</strong><p>For f(g(x)) to be defined, x must be allowed in g and g(x) must be allowed in f. This two-stage check is vital with logs and roots.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated. These notes normalise obvious garbled mathematical phrases, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>"
