        "contentHtml": "<section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul><li>translate between diagrams, unit-circle facts, and trig equations.</li><li>Set up the mathematical model before calculating.</li><li>Track restrictions, units, signs, or intervals.</li><li>Write answers in context rather than as unexplained algebra.</li></ul></section><section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on revision: quadratics, inequalities, and trigonometry. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Revision: quadratics, inequalities, and trigonometry</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Revision move</strong><p>Redo the method cards on paper and compare your setup, restrictions, and interpretation.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Answer checks</strong><p>Check domains, signs, units, intervals, and graph behaviour before accepting a result.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Quadratic revision</h2>\n<p>Revision connects factorising, completing the square, quadratic formula, and sketching. The best method depends on the question.</p>\n<div class=\"table-wrap\"><table><tr><th>Task</th><th>Tool</th></tr><tr><td>Easy roots</td><td>Factorise</td></tr><tr><td>Vertex</td><td>Complete the square</td></tr><tr><td>Any roots</td><td>Quadratic formula</td></tr><tr><td>Sketch</td><td>Combine intercepts, vertex, and opening direction</td></tr></table></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Trig revision</h2>\n<p>Special triangles, the unit circle, and sine-wave graphs are three views of the same trig information. Use the unit circle for signs outside the first quadrant.</p>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol><li>Locate the quadrant.</li><li>Use the reference angle.</li><li>Apply the sign of sine or cosine.</li><li>List all solutions in the interval.</li></ol></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Inequality revision</h2>\n<p>Inequalities return intervals. The important points are zeros, undefined values, and endpoints where the inequality may or may not include equality.</p>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol><li>Move to one side and compare with zero.</li><li>Find zeros and undefined points.</li><li>Build a sign chart.</li><li>Select intervals matching the inequality.</li></ol></div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Common mistakes</strong><ul><li>Do not include denominator zeros.</li><li>Remember to flip the sign if multiplying by a known negative.</li></ul></div>\n</section><section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Quadratic revision</strong><p>Revision connects factorising, completing the square, quadratic formula, and sketching. The best method depends on the question.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Trig revision</strong><p>Special triangles, the unit circle, and sine-wave graphs are three views of the same trig information. Use the unit circle for signs outside the first quadrant.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Inequality revision</strong><p>Inequalities return intervals. The important points are zeros, undefined values, and endpoints where the inequality may or may not include equality.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated. These notes normalise obvious garbled mathematical phrases, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>"
