        "contentHtml": "<section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul><li>identify inputs, outputs, domains, and composition structure.</li><li>Set up the mathematical model before calculating.</li><li>Track restrictions, units, signs, or intervals.</li><li>Write answers in context rather than as unexplained algebra.</li></ul></section><section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on exponential and logarithmic functions. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Exponential and logarithmic functions</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Revision move</strong><p>Redo the method cards on paper and compare your setup, restrictions, and interpretation.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Answer checks</strong><p>Check domains, signs, units, intervals, and graph behaviour before accepting a result.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Exponential functions</h2>\n<p>An exponential has the variable in the exponent. Its base controls multiplicative growth or decay, and the graph has a horizontal asymptote.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>f(x)=b^x, b&gt;0, b not equal 1<br>b^(x+y)=b^x b^y<br>b^0=1</div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Logarithms</h2>\n<p>A logarithm asks what exponent is needed. It is the inverse operation to exponentiation, so its domain is positive inputs only.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>log_b(x)=y means b^y=x<br>log_b(xy)=log_b(x)+log_b(y)<br>log_b(x^p)=p log_b(x)</div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Common mistakes</strong><ul><li>log(a+b) is not log(a)+log(b).</li></ul></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Inverse functions</h2>\n<p>Inverse functions undo one another. Exponential and logarithmic functions are the main inverse pair in this part of the course.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>b^(log_b x)=x, x&gt;0<br>log_b(b^x)=x</div>\n</section><section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Exponential functions</strong><p>An exponential has the variable in the exponent. Its base controls multiplicative growth or decay, and the graph has a horizontal asymptote.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Logarithms</strong><p>A logarithm asks what exponent is needed. It is the inverse operation to exponentiation, so its domain is positive inputs only.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Inverse functions</strong><p>Inverse functions undo one another. Exponential and logarithmic functions are the main inverse pair in this part of the course.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated. These notes normalise obvious garbled mathematical phrases, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>"
