        "subtitle": "This lecture focuses on limits and derivative from first principles. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.",
        "contentHtml": "<section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul><li>explain limiting behaviour and its role in derivatives.</li><li>choose and apply the correct differentiation rule.</li><li>Set up the mathematical model before calculating.</li><li>Track restrictions, units, signs, or intervals.</li><li>Write answers in context rather than as unexplained algebra.</li></ul></section><section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on limits and derivative from first principles. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Limits and derivative from first principles</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Revision move</strong><p>Redo the method cards on paper and compare your setup, restrictions, and interpretation.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Answer checks</strong><p>Check domains, signs, units, intervals, and graph behaviour before accepting a result.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Limits</h2>\n<p>A limit describes the value a function approaches as the input approaches a point. The function value at the point may be different or absent.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>lim_{x-&gt;a} f(x)=L<br>left and right limits must agree</div>\n<div class=\"diagram\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 340 200\"><line x1=\"35\" y1=\"160\" x2=\"310\" y2=\"160\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><path d=\"M70 140 C120 100 160 80 230 55\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#2563eb\" stroke-width=\"3\"/><circle cx=\"170\" cy=\"80\" r=\"6\" fill=\"#fff\" stroke=\"#2563eb\" stroke-width=\"3\"/><circle cx=\"170\" cy=\"120\" r=\"5\" fill=\"#0f766e\"/><text x=\"185\" y=\"83\" font-size=\"12\">approached</text><text x=\"185\" y=\"123\" font-size=\"12\">actual</text></svg></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Derivative from first principles</h2>\n<p>First-principles differentiation expands f(x+h), cancels the original f(x) terms, cancels h, and only then takes the limit.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>f&#x27;(x)=lim_{h-&gt;0} [f(x+h)-f(x)]/h<br>For f(x)=x^2, the quotient simplifies to 2x+h, so the derivative is 2x.</div>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol><li>Write the limit definition.</li><li>Substitute f(x+h) and f(x).</li><li>Expand and simplify.</li><li>Factor and cancel h.</li><li>Let h approach zero.</li></ol></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Slope as velocity</h2>\n<p>For displacement versus time, slope is velocity. A second derivative gives acceleration, so derivative notation has a direct kinematics interpretation.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>v(t)=ds/dt<br>a(t)=dv/dt=d^2s/dt^2</div>\n</section><section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Limits</strong><p>A limit describes the value a function approaches as the input approaches a point. The function value at the point may be different or absent.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Derivative from first principles</strong><p>First-principles differentiation expands f(x+h), cancels the original f(x) terms, cancels h, and only then takes the limit.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Slope as velocity</strong><p>For displacement versus time, slope is velocity. A second derivative gives acceleration, so derivative notation has a direct kinematics interpretation.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated. These notes normalise obvious garbled mathematical phrases, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>"
