        "contentHtml": "<section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul><li>choose and apply the correct differentiation rule.</li><li>Set up the mathematical model before calculating.</li><li>Track restrictions, units, signs, or intervals.</li><li>Write answers in context rather than as unexplained algebra.</li></ul></section><section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on power rule and first-principles differentiation. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Power rule and first-principles differentiation</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Revision move</strong><p>Redo the method cards on paper and compare your setup, restrictions, and interpretation.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Answer checks</strong><p>Check domains, signs, units, intervals, and graph behaviour before accepting a result.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Derivative from first principles</h2>\n<p>First-principles differentiation expands f(x+h), cancels the original f(x) terms, cancels h, and only then takes the limit.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>f&#x27;(x)=lim_{h-&gt;0} [f(x+h)-f(x)]/h<br>For f(x)=x^2, the quotient simplifies to 2x+h, so the derivative is 2x.</div>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol><li>Write the limit definition.</li><li>Substitute f(x+h) and f(x).</li><li>Expand and simplify.</li><li>Factor and cancel h.</li><li>Let h approach zero.</li></ol></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Power rule</h2>\n<p>After deriving simple powers from first principles, the power rule gives a fast method for polynomials. Constants multiply through differentiation.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>d/dx x^n = n x^(n-1)<br>d/dx c = 0</div>\n<div class=\"table-wrap\"><table><tr><th>Function</th><th>Derivative</th></tr><tr><td>x^2</td><td>2x</td></tr><tr><td>x^3</td><td>3x^2</td></tr><tr><td>5x^4</td><td>20x^3</td></tr></table></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Basic derivative table</h2>\n<p>Derivative tables are recognition tools. The work is choosing the right row and combining it with product, quotient, or chain rules as needed.</p>\n<div class=\"table-wrap\"><table><tr><th>f(x)</th><th>f&#x27;(x)</th></tr><tr><td>x^n</td><td>n x^(n-1)</td></tr><tr><td>sin x</td><td>cos x</td></tr><tr><td>cos x</td><td>-sin x</td></tr><tr><td>e^x</td><td>e^x</td></tr><tr><td>ln x</td><td>1/x</td></tr></table></div>\n</section><section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Derivative from first principles</strong><p>First-principles differentiation expands f(x+h), cancels the original f(x) terms, cancels h, and only then takes the limit.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Power rule</strong><p>After deriving simple powers from first principles, the power rule gives a fast method for polynomials. Constants multiply through differentiation.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Basic derivative table</strong><p>Derivative tables are recognition tools. The work is choosing the right row and combining it with product, quotient, or chain rules as needed.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated. These notes normalise obvious garbled mathematical phrases, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>"
