        "contentHtml": "<section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul><li>translate between diagrams, unit-circle facts, and trig equations.</li><li>choose and apply the correct differentiation rule.</li><li>Set up the mathematical model before calculating.</li><li>Track restrictions, units, signs, or intervals.</li><li>Write answers in context rather than as unexplained algebra.</li></ul></section><section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on product, quotient, trig, and chain rules. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Product, quotient, trig, and chain rules</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Revision move</strong><p>Redo the method cards on paper and compare your setup, restrictions, and interpretation.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Answer checks</strong><p>Check domains, signs, units, intervals, and graph behaviour before accepting a result.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Product rule</h2>\n<p>Use the product rule when two variable-dependent functions are multiplied. Name the factors before differentiating.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>(fg)&#x27;=f&#x27;g+fg&#x27;</div>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol><li>Set f and g.</li><li>Find f prime and g prime.</li><li>Substitute into f prime g plus f g prime.</li><li>Simplify after the structure is correct.</li></ol></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Quotient rule</h2>\n<p>Use the quotient rule for a function divided by another function. The subtraction order in the numerator matters.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>(f/g)&#x27;=(f&#x27;g-fg&#x27;)/g^2</div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Common mistakes</strong><ul><li>Do not reverse f prime g minus f g prime.</li><li>Do not forget the denominator squared.</li></ul></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Trig derivatives</h2>\n<p>The core trig derivative facts are sine to cosine and cosine to negative sine. These formulas assume radian input.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>d/dx sin x = cos x<br>d/dx cos x = -sin x<br>d/dx tan x = sec^2 x</div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Chain rule</h2>\n<p>The chain rule differentiates a function of a function. The lecture repeatedly asks for the inner function because its derivative must be multiplied.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>If y=f(u), u=g(x), then dy/dx=(dy/du)(du/dx)<br>d/dx sin(x^2)=2x cos(x^2)</div>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol><li>Choose the inner function u.</li><li>Differentiate the outside with respect to u.</li><li>Differentiate u with respect to x.</li><li>Multiply and substitute back.</li></ol></div>\n</section><section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Product rule</strong><p>Use the product rule when two variable-dependent functions are multiplied. Name the factors before differentiating.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Quotient rule</strong><p>Use the quotient rule for a function divided by another function. The subtraction order in the numerator matters.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Trig derivatives</strong><p>The core trig derivative facts are sine to cosine and cosine to negative sine. These formulas assume radian input.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Chain rule</strong><p>The chain rule differentiates a function of a function. The lecture repeatedly asks for the inner function because its derivative must be multiplied.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated. These notes normalise obvious garbled mathematical phrases, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>"
