        "contentHtml": "<section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul><li>choose and apply the correct differentiation rule.</li><li>Set up the mathematical model before calculating.</li><li>Track restrictions, units, signs, or intervals.</li><li>Write answers in context rather than as unexplained algebra.</li></ul></section><section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on curve sketching using derivatives. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Curve sketching using derivatives</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Revision move</strong><p>Redo the method cards on paper and compare your setup, restrictions, and interpretation.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Answer checks</strong><p>Check domains, signs, units, intervals, and graph behaviour before accepting a result.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Critical points</h2>\n<p>Critical points include derivative-zero points and places where the derivative is undefined while the function exists. They must be tested, not assumed.</p>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol><li>Find f prime.</li><li>Solve f prime equals zero.</li><li>Find derivative undefined points in the domain.</li><li>Use sign or second derivative tests.</li></ol></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>First derivative sign test</h2>\n<p>A positive derivative means increasing; a negative derivative means decreasing. Sign changes classify stationary points.</p>\n<div class=\"table-wrap\"><table><tr><th>f prime sign</th><th>Behaviour</th><th>Classification</th></tr><tr><td>+ to -</td><td>increasing then decreasing</td><td>local maximum</td></tr><tr><td>- to +</td><td>decreasing then increasing</td><td>local minimum</td></tr><tr><td>no sign change</td><td>keeps increasing/decreasing</td><td>not a turning point</td></tr></table></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Curve sketching with derivatives</h2>\n<p>Derivative information turns a sketch into a reasoned graph. First derivative gives increasing/decreasing intervals; second derivative gives concavity.</p>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol><li>Find domain and intercepts.</li><li>Find critical points.</li><li>Build derivative sign intervals.</li><li>Check concavity if required.</li><li>Sketch labelled features.</li></ol></div>\n</section><section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Critical points</strong><p>Critical points include derivative-zero points and places where the derivative is undefined while the function exists. They must be tested, not assumed.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>First derivative sign test</strong><p>A positive derivative means increasing; a negative derivative means decreasing. Sign changes classify stationary points.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Curve sketching with derivatives</strong><p>Derivative information turns a sketch into a reasoned graph. First derivative gives increasing/decreasing intervals; second derivative gives concavity.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated. These notes normalise obvious garbled mathematical phrases, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>"
