        "contentHtml": "<section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul><li>choose and apply the correct differentiation rule.</li><li>model a maximum/minimum problem and test candidates.</li><li>Set up the mathematical model before calculating.</li><li>Track restrictions, units, signs, or intervals.</li><li>Write answers in context rather than as unexplained algebra.</li></ul></section><section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on open-box optimisation and domain checks. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Open-box optimisation and domain checks</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Revision move</strong><p>Redo the method cards on paper and compare your setup, restrictions, and interpretation.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Answer checks</strong><p>Check domains, signs, units, intervals, and graph behaviour before accepting a result.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Open-box optimisation</h2>\n<p>Cutting equal squares from a sheet makes the cut size x the box height. The remaining length and width are reduced by 2x.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>V(x)=x(L-2x)(W-2x)<br>for a 30 cm square, V(x)=x(30-2x)^2<br>0&lt;=x&lt;=15</div>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol><li>Draw the sheet and cuts.</li><li>Write new dimensions.</li><li>Form volume.</li><li>Differentiate.</li><li>Use domain to reject impossible candidates.</li></ol></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Domain checks</h2>\n<p>A derivative candidate can be algebraically valid but physically impossible. In the box problem, endpoints can give zero volume and should be compared, not blindly accepted.</p>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Common mistakes</strong><ul><li>Do not accept x outside the feasible interval.</li><li>Do not call a zero-volume endpoint the useful maximum.</li></ul></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Second derivative test</h2>\n<p>At a stationary point, a positive second derivative indicates concave up and usually a local minimum; a negative second derivative indicates concave down and usually a local maximum.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>f prime(c)=0 and f double-prime(c)&gt;0: local minimum<br>f prime(c)=0 and f double-prime(c)&lt;0: local maximum</div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Common mistakes</strong><ul><li>If f double-prime(c)=0, the test is inconclusive.</li></ul></div>\n</section><section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Open-box optimisation</strong><p>Cutting equal squares from a sheet makes the cut size x the box height. The remaining length and width are reduced by 2x.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Domain checks</strong><p>A derivative candidate can be algebraically valid but physically impossible. In the box problem, endpoints can give zero volume and should be compared, not blindly accept</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Second derivative test</strong><p>At a stationary point, a positive second derivative indicates concave up and usually a local minimum; a negative second derivative indicates concave down and usually a lo</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated. These notes normalise obvious garbled mathematical phrases, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>"
