        "title": "Integration as signed area",
        "subtitle": "This lecture focuses on integration as signed area. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.",
        "contentHtml": "<section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul><li>Set up the mathematical model before calculating.</li><li>Track restrictions, units, signs, or intervals.</li><li>Write answers in context rather than as unexplained algebra.</li></ul></section><section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on integration as signed area. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Integration as signed area</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Revision move</strong><p>Redo the method cards on paper and compare your setup, restrictions, and interpretation.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Answer checks</strong><p>Check domains, signs, units, intervals, and graph behaviour before accepting a result.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Integration as area accumulation</h2>\n<p>Integration begins as area under a curve. When the curve represents velocity, the area represents displacement.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>area under y=f(x) from a to b = integral_a^b f(x) dx<br>constant velocity distance = velocity*time</div>\n<div class=\"diagram\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 360 220\"><line x1=\"35\" y1=\"175\" x2=\"330\" y2=\"175\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><path d=\"M85 160 C130 70 225 60 295 120 L295 175 L85 175 Z\" fill=\"#dbeafe\"/><path d=\"M85 160 C130 70 225 60 295 120\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#2563eb\" stroke-width=\"3\"/><text x=\"145\" y=\"150\" font-size=\"12\">accumulated area</text></svg></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Velocity-time area</h2>\n<p>Area under a velocity-time graph gives displacement. If velocity is always positive, that also equals distance travelled.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>displacement=integral v(t) dt<br>distance may require integral |v(t)| dt if direction changes</div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Trapezium approximations</h2>\n<p>Before exact integration, areas can be approximated by rectangles or trapeziums. Trapeziums account for a sloping top edge.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>trapezium area=(1/2)(parallel side 1 + parallel side 2)*width<br>Riemann sum=sum f(x_i) Delta x</div>\n<div class=\"diagram\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 360 200\"><line x1=\"35\" y1=\"160\" x2=\"330\" y2=\"160\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><path d=\"M60 150 C125 80 220 65 310 115\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#2563eb\" stroke-width=\"3\"/><path d=\"M60 160 L60 150 L120 105 L120 160 Z M120 160 L120 105 L180 82 L180 160 Z M180 160 L180 82 L240 82 L240 160 Z M240 160 L240 82 L300 110 L300 160 Z\" fill=\"#ecfdf5\" stroke=\"#0f766e\"/></svg></div>\n</section><section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Integration as area accumulation</strong><p>Integration begins as area under a curve. When the curve represents velocity, the area represents displacement.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Velocity-time area</strong><p>Area under a velocity-time graph gives displacement. If velocity is always positive, that also equals distance travelled.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Trapezium approximations</strong><p>Before exact integration, areas can be approximated by rectangles or trapeziums. Trapeziums account for a sloping top edge.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated. These notes normalise obvious garbled mathematical phrases, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>"
