        "title": "Signed area and definite integrals",
        "subtitle": "This lecture focuses on signed area and definite integrals. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.",
        "contentHtml": "<section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul><li>interpret integrals as signed area or accumulated change.</li><li>Set up the mathematical model before calculating.</li><li>Track restrictions, units, signs, or intervals.</li><li>Write answers in context rather than as unexplained algebra.</li></ul></section><section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on signed area and definite integrals. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Signed area and definite integrals</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Revision move</strong><p>Redo the method cards on paper and compare your setup, restrictions, and interpretation.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Answer checks</strong><p>Check domains, signs, units, intervals, and graph behaviour before accepting a result.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Signed area</h2>\n<p>Definite integrals count area above the axis positive and area below the axis negative. Geometric area uses absolute value and may require splitting the interval.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>signed area=integral_a^b f(x) dx<br>geometric area=integral_a^b |f(x)| dx</div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Common mistakes</strong><ul><li>A signed integral of zero can still enclose nonzero geometric area.</li></ul></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Trapezium approximations</h2>\n<p>Before exact integration, areas can be approximated by rectangles or trapeziums. Trapeziums account for a sloping top edge.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>trapezium area=(1/2)(parallel side 1 + parallel side 2)*width<br>Riemann sum=sum f(x_i) Delta x</div>\n<div class=\"diagram\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 360 200\"><line x1=\"35\" y1=\"160\" x2=\"330\" y2=\"160\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><path d=\"M60 150 C125 80 220 65 310 115\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#2563eb\" stroke-width=\"3\"/><path d=\"M60 160 L60 150 L120 105 L120 160 Z M120 160 L120 105 L180 82 L180 160 Z M180 160 L180 82 L240 82 L240 160 Z M240 160 L240 82 L300 110 L300 160 Z\" fill=\"#ecfdf5\" stroke=\"#0f766e\"/></svg></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Definite integrals</h2>\n<p>A definite integral returns a number. Find an antiderivative, evaluate upper minus lower, and interpret the units.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>integral_a^b f(x) dx = F(b)-F(a), where F prime=f</div>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol><li>Find F.</li><li>Evaluate at the upper limit.</li><li>Evaluate at the lower limit.</li><li>Subtract lower from upper.</li></ol></div>\n</section><section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Signed area</strong><p>Definite integrals count area above the axis positive and area below the axis negative. Geometric area uses absolute value and may require splitting the interval.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Trapezium approximations</strong><p>Before exact integration, areas can be approximated by rectangles or trapeziums. Trapeziums account for a sloping top edge.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Definite integrals</strong><p>A definite integral returns a number. Find an antiderivative, evaluate upper minus lower, and interpret the units.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated. These notes normalise obvious garbled mathematical phrases, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>"
