        "contentHtml": "<section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul><li>choose and apply the correct differentiation rule.</li><li>use substitution as reverse chain rule.</li><li>Set up the mathematical model before calculating.</li><li>Track restrictions, units, signs, or intervals.</li><li>Write answers in context rather than as unexplained algebra.</li></ul></section><section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on antiderivatives and substitution begins. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Antiderivatives and substitution begins</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Revision move</strong><p>Redo the method cards on paper and compare your setup, restrictions, and interpretation.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Answer checks</strong><p>Check domains, signs, units, intervals, and graph behaviour before accepting a result.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Antiderivatives</h2>\n<p>An antiderivative reverses differentiation. Indefinite integrals need +C because constants differentiate to zero.</p>\n<div class=\"table-wrap\"><table><tr><th>Integrand</th><th>Antiderivative</th></tr><tr><td>x^n, n not -1</td><td>x^(n+1)/(n+1)+C</td></tr><tr><td>cos x</td><td>sin x+C</td></tr><tr><td>sin x</td><td>-cos x+C</td></tr><tr><td>1/x</td><td>ln|x|+C</td></tr><tr><td>e^x</td><td>e^x+C</td></tr></table></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Reverse chain rule</h2>\n<p>Substitution starts by recognising a composite function whose inner derivative is also present. That pattern reverses the chain rule.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>let u=g(x), du=g prime(x) dx<br>integral f(g(x))g prime(x) dx becomes integral f(u) du</div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Substitution</h2>\n<p>Substitution changes variables so a composite integrand becomes a basic integral. The differential du must match the leftover dx factor.</p>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol><li>Choose u as the inner function.</li><li>Compute du.</li><li>Rewrite the integral entirely in u.</li><li>Integrate.</li><li>Substitute back or change limits.</li></ol></div>\n</section><section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Antiderivatives</strong><p>An antiderivative reverses differentiation. Indefinite integrals need +C because constants differentiate to zero.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Reverse chain rule</strong><p>Substitution starts by recognising a composite function whose inner derivative is also present. That pattern reverses the chain rule.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Substitution</strong><p>Substitution changes variables so a composite integrand becomes a basic integral. The differential du must match the leftover dx factor.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated. These notes normalise obvious garbled mathematical phrases, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>"
