        "subtitle": "This lecture focuses on integration by substitution. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.",
        "contentHtml": "<section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul><li>use substitution as reverse chain rule.</li><li>Set up the mathematical model before calculating.</li><li>Track restrictions, units, signs, or intervals.</li><li>Write answers in context rather than as unexplained algebra.</li></ul></section><section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on integration by substitution. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Integration by substitution</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Revision move</strong><p>Redo the method cards on paper and compare your setup, restrictions, and interpretation.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Answer checks</strong><p>Check domains, signs, units, intervals, and graph behaviour before accepting a result.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Substitution</h2>\n<p>Substitution changes variables so a composite integrand becomes a basic integral. The differential du must match the leftover dx factor.</p>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol><li>Choose u as the inner function.</li><li>Compute du.</li><li>Rewrite the integral entirely in u.</li><li>Integrate.</li><li>Substitute back or change limits.</li></ol></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Substitution examples</h2>\n<p>The lecture examples use inner functions such as x^2, 4x, or a linear expression. Constants can be adjusted when du is a constant multiple of the available factor.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>If u=x^2, then du=2x dx, so 6x dx=3 du.<br>If u=4x+1, then du=4 dx, so dx=(1/4)du.</div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Common mistakes</strong><ul><li>Do not leave x terms in a u-integral.</li><li>Do not forget to substitute back for indefinite integrals.</li></ul></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Clean substitution layout</h2>\n<p>A substitution solution should make every replacement visible. This prevents mixing x-limits with u-integrands.</p>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol><li>Write u=...</li><li>Write du=... dx.</li><li>Replace every x-expression in the integral.</li><li>Integrate in u.</li><li>Back-substitute or evaluate using changed limits.</li></ol></div>\n</section><section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Substitution</strong><p>Substitution changes variables so a composite integrand becomes a basic integral. The differential du must match the leftover dx factor.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Substitution examples</strong><p>The lecture examples use inner functions such as x^2, 4x, or a linear expression. Constants can be adjusted when du is a constant multiple of the available factor.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Clean substitution layout</strong><p>A substitution solution should make every replacement visible. This prevents mixing x-limits with u-integrands.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated. These notes normalise obvious garbled mathematical phrases, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>"
