        "title": "Kinematics by integration",
        "subtitle": "This lecture focuses on kinematics by integration. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.",
        "contentHtml": "<section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul><li>interpret integrals as signed area or accumulated change.</li><li>connect displacement, velocity, and acceleration.</li><li>Set up the mathematical model before calculating.</li><li>Track restrictions, units, signs, or intervals.</li><li>Write answers in context rather than as unexplained algebra.</li></ul></section><section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on kinematics by integration. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Kinematics by integration</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Revision move</strong><p>Redo the method cards on paper and compare your setup, restrictions, and interpretation.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Answer checks</strong><p>Check domains, signs, units, intervals, and graph behaviour before accepting a result.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Kinematics by integration</h2>\n<p>If acceleration is known, integrate to obtain velocity; integrate again to obtain displacement. Initial conditions determine constants.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>a(t)=s double-prime(t)<br>v(t)=integral a(t) dt<br>s(t)=integral v(t) dt</div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Initial conditions</h2>\n<p>An initial condition gives the missing constant after integration. Substitute the known time and known value after integrating.</p>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol><li>Integrate and include +C.</li><li>Substitute the initial condition.</li><li>Solve for C.</li><li>Write the particular function.</li></ol></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Constant acceleration model</h2>\n<p>For constant acceleration, velocity is linear in time and displacement is quadratic. The constants are initial velocity and initial displacement.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>v(t)=at+v0<br>s(t)=(1/2)at^2+v0 t+s0</div>\n</section><section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Kinematics by integration</strong><p>If acceleration is known, integrate to obtain velocity; integrate again to obtain displacement. Initial conditions determine constants.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Initial conditions</strong><p>An initial condition gives the missing constant after integration. Substitute the known time and known value after integrating.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Constant acceleration model</strong><p>For constant acceleration, velocity is linear in time and displacement is quadratic. The constants are initial velocity and initial displacement.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated. These notes normalise obvious garbled mathematical phrases, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>"
