        "contentHtml": "<section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul><li>explain limiting behaviour and its role in derivatives.</li><li>interpret integrals as signed area or accumulated change.</li><li>Set up the mathematical model before calculating.</li><li>Track restrictions, units, signs, or intervals.</li><li>Write answers in context rather than as unexplained algebra.</li></ul></section><section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on definite integrals, symmetry, and area. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Definite integrals, symmetry, and area</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Revision move</strong><p>Redo the method cards on paper and compare your setup, restrictions, and interpretation.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Answer checks</strong><p>Check domains, signs, units, intervals, and graph behaviour before accepting a result.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Limits of integration</h2>\n<p>The upper and lower numbers on a definite integral mark the interval of accumulation. They are not the same concept as a limiting process, despite the shared word.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>integral_a^b f(x) dx uses lower a and upper b<br>integral_b^a f(x) dx = - integral_a^b f(x) dx</div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Odd and even symmetry</h2>\n<p>Symmetry can simplify definite integrals. Odd functions cancel on symmetric intervals; even functions double the half-interval area.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>odd: f(-x)=-f(x), integral_-a^a f(x) dx=0<br>even: f(-x)=f(x), integral_-a^a f(x) dx=2 integral_0^a f(x) dx</div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Area under a curve</h2>\n<p>Exact area uses definite integrals. A sketch tells whether the curve crosses the axis and whether signed or geometric area is wanted.</p>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol><li>Sketch the region.</li><li>Find crossings if sign changes matter.</li><li>Choose signed or geometric area.</li><li>Integrate over the correct intervals.</li></ol></div>\n</section><section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Limits of integration</strong><p>The upper and lower numbers on a definite integral mark the interval of accumulation. They are not the same concept as a limiting process, despite the shared word.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Odd and even symmetry</strong><p>Symmetry can simplify definite integrals. Odd functions cancel on symmetric intervals; even functions double the half-interval area.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Area under a curve</strong><p>Exact area uses definite integrals. A sketch tells whether the curve crosses the axis and whether signed or geometric area is wanted.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated. These notes normalise obvious garbled mathematical phrases, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>"
