        "contentHtml": "<section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul><li>recover accumulated quantities from rates.</li><li>Set up the mathematical model before calculating.</li><li>Track restrictions, units, signs, or intervals.</li><li>Write answers in context rather than as unexplained algebra.</li></ul></section><section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on applied rates and accumulated quantities. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Applied rates and accumulated quantities</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Revision move</strong><p>Redo the method cards on paper and compare your setup, restrictions, and interpretation.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Answer checks</strong><p>Check domains, signs, units, intervals, and graph behaviour before accepting a result.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Applied rates</h2>\n<p>A rate function has units per time. Integrating it over time gives accumulated quantity. This is the common structure behind revenue, population, volume, and motion examples.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>total change = integral_a^b rate(t) dt<br>If R(t)=10000 sqrt(1+t) dollars/year, total revenue is integral R(t) dt</div>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol><li>Identify rate and units.</li><li>Identify interval.</li><li>Integrate the rate.</li><li>Check resulting units.</li></ol></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Recovering quantity from rate</h2>\n<p>If a derivative or rate is given and the original quantity is requested, integrate. Use an initial value to determine the constant.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>If N prime(t)=r(t), then N(t)=integral r(t)dt+C</div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Initial conditions</h2>\n<p>An initial condition gives the missing constant after integration. Substitute the known time and known value after integrating.</p>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol><li>Integrate and include +C.</li><li>Substitute the initial condition.</li><li>Solve for C.</li><li>Write the particular function.</li></ol></div>\n</section><section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Applied rates</strong><p>A rate function has units per time. Integrating it over time gives accumulated quantity. This is the common structure behind revenue, population, volume, and motion examp</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Recovering quantity from rate</strong><p>If a derivative or rate is given and the original quantity is requested, integrate. Use an initial value to determine the constant.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Initial conditions</strong><p>An initial condition gives the missing constant after integration. Substitute the known time and known value after integrating.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated. These notes normalise obvious garbled mathematical phrases, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>"
