        "contentHtml": "<section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2><ul><li>choose and apply the correct differentiation rule.</li><li>recover accumulated quantities from rates.</li><li>compute and graph complex numbers.</li><li>Set up the mathematical model before calculating.</li><li>Track restrictions, units, signs, or intervals.</li></ul></section><section><h2>Overview</h2><p>This lecture focuses on final revision: rates, complex numbers, and quadratics. The notes below organise the lecture flow into methods, formulas, worked-example patterns, and checks for revision.</p><div class=\"summary-grid\"><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Main thread</strong><p>Final revision: rates, complex numbers, and quadratics</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Revision move</strong><p>Redo the method cards on paper and compare your setup, restrictions, and interpretation.</p></div><div class=\"note-card\"><strong>Answer checks</strong><p>Check domains, signs, units, intervals, and graph behaviour before accepting a result.</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Applied rates</h2>\n<p>A rate function has units per time. Integrating it over time gives accumulated quantity. This is the common structure behind revenue, population, volume, and motion examples.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>total change = integral_a^b rate(t) dt<br>If R(t)=10000 sqrt(1+t) dollars/year, total revenue is integral R(t) dt</div>\n<div class=\"method\"><strong>Method</strong><ol><li>Identify rate and units.</li><li>Identify interval.</li><li>Integrate the rate.</li><li>Check resulting units.</li></ol></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Complex number review</h2>\n<p>Complex arithmetic keeps real and imaginary parts separate. Multiplication uses expansion and then i^2=-1.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>(a+bi)+(c+di)=(a+c)+(b+d)i<br>(a+bi)(c+di)=(ac-bd)+(ad+bc)i<br>i^2=-1</div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Common mistakes</strong><ul><li>Do not combine real and imaginary parts as like terms.</li></ul></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Argand diagram and exponential form</h2>\n<p>On an Argand diagram, a+bi is the point (a,b). The modulus is distance from the origin and the argument is angle from the positive real axis.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>r=sqrt(a^2+b^2)<br>z=r e^(i theta)</div>\n<div class=\"diagram\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 320 240\"><line x1=\"35\" y1=\"170\" x2=\"295\" y2=\"170\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><line x1=\"120\" y1=\"215\" x2=\"120\" y2=\"35\" stroke=\"#667085\"/><path d=\"M120 170 L230 85\" stroke=\"#7c3aed\" stroke-width=\"3\"/><circle cx=\"230\" cy=\"85\" r=\"5\" fill=\"#0f766e\"/><text x=\"235\" y=\"85\" font-size=\"12\">a+bi</text><text x=\"260\" y=\"188\" font-size=\"12\">real</text><text x=\"125\" y=\"45\" font-size=\"12\">imaginary</text></svg></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Complex roots of quadratics</h2>\n<p>A quadratic with negative discriminant has no real roots but still has complex roots. Completing the square exposes this cleanly.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>(x-1)^2+4=0<br>(x-1)^2=-4<br>x=1 +/- 2i</div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Common mistakes</strong><ul><li>Do not stop at no real solution when complex answers are requested.</li></ul></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Second derivative test</h2>\n<p>At a stationary point, a positive second derivative indicates concave up and usually a local minimum; a negative second derivative indicates concave down and usually a local maximum.</p>\n<div class=\"formula\"><strong>Formula focus</strong><br>f prime(c)=0 and f double-prime(c)&gt;0: local minimum<br>f prime(c)=0 and f double-prime(c)&lt;0: local maximum</div>\n<div class=\"callout warning\"><strong>Common mistakes</strong><ul><li>If f double-prime(c)=0, the test is inconclusive.</li></ul></div>\n</section><section><h2>Key Terms</h2><div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Applied rates</strong><p>A rate function has units per time. Integrating it over time gives accumulated quantity. This is the common structure behind revenue, population, volume, and motion examp</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Complex number review</strong><p>Complex arithmetic keeps real and imaginary parts separate. Multiplication uses expansion and then i^2=-1.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Argand diagram and exponential form</strong><p>On an Argand diagram, a+bi is the point (a,b). The modulus is distance from the origin and the argument is angle from the positive real axis.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Complex roots of quadratics</strong><p>A quadratic with negative discriminant has no real roots but still has complex roots. Completing the square exposes this cleanly.</p></div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Second derivative test</strong><p>At a stationary point, a positive second derivative indicates concave up and usually a local minimum; a negative second derivative indicates concave down and usually a lo</p></div></div></section><section><h2>Transcript Caveats</h2><div class=\"callout warning\"><p>The transcript is machine-generated. These notes normalise obvious garbled mathematical phrases, but ambiguous algebra should be checked against the audio or lecture slides.</p></div></section>"
