        "contentHtml": "\n<section>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>This lecture combines library research guidance with a careful discussion of AI as a tool. The key study point is not whether AI is good or bad in the abstract, but how engineers verify, attribute, limit, and ethically use tools while solving and communicating a problem.</p>\n<div class=\"callout\"><strong>Capture note.</strong> This static page was written from this folder&#x27;s transcript and metadata. Capture: Alternate capture; media id 80a1f43d-7bf3-4f1a-8a89-45dcec98add0; transcript segments 1421; approx. transcript words 7476.</div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2>\n<ul><li>Use library and source-evaluation support to find credible evidence for Assignment 1.</li><li>Explain the benefits and limitations of generative AI in academic and engineering work.</li><li>Apply validation, attribution, and disclosure when AI is permitted.</li><li>Keep the engineering process visible when comparing solutions to liquefaction or EWB-style problems.</li></ul>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Detailed Study Notes</h2>\n<h3>Assignment context: process matters</h3>\n<p>The lecture opens by tying Assignment 1 to the first five steps of the engineering process and the problem of soil liquefaction. Students are not simply asked to produce a polished answer; they are asked to show how they think about the problem, locate evidence, compare solutions, and use AI within declared boundaries.</p>\n<p>The library segment reinforces that the assignment is deliberately scoped. You do not need a PhD-level solution to liquefaction. You need credible sources, a clear comparison of two possible responses, and a defensible process for deciding what fits the environment.</p>\n<h3>Finding and judging sources</h3>\n<p>Library support is framed as part of engineering practice. Students are pointed toward databases, APA referencing help, tutorials, workshops, one-to-one support, and live chat. The most important skill is not collecting many sources; it is judging whether a source deserves to influence a design decision.</p>\n<p>The CRAAP test is introduced as a practical filter: currency, reliability or relevance, authority, accuracy/equity, and purpose. The lecturer&#x27;s simple rule is memorable: if you cannot find an author and a year, be cautious. In engineering reports, weak evidence creates weak recommendations.</p>\n<h3>AI as a tool, not a substitute</h3>\n<p>The lecturer takes a deliberately neutral stance. AI exists, industry asks how graduates are being taught to use it, and students will encounter it. But a tool does not become an engineer. AI can help brainstorm, summarize, translate, support accessibility, critique drafts, or handle broad information searches, but it cannot own the judgement, responsibility, or final verification.</p>\n<p>The lecture models disclosure by saying the AI lecture was initially generated with ChatGPT, then edited and supplemented. That example sets the assignment standard: if AI shaped your work, say so, explain how, and make sure the final reasoning is yours.</p>\n<h3>Limitations and ethical concerns</h3>\n<p>Students identify hallucination, knowledge pollution, and resource use as reasons to distrust or dislike AI. The lecturer agrees these are real concerns. The engineering response is not blind adoption; it is risk control. Check claims against sources, use specialist tools only where appropriate, and avoid relying on AI in areas where you cannot detect errors.</p>\n<p>Automated grading is discussed as a useful contrast. AI may be attractive for speed, but students object to it marking nuanced reports. That distinction is important: tasks with clear right answers may tolerate automation better than design reports where context, judgement, and justification matter.</p>\n<h3>Using AI in engineering work</h3>\n<p>Good uses include brainstorming possible stakeholders or solution categories, asking for draft critique against a rubric, simplifying dense explanations for first-pass learning, and helping with language accessibility. Weak uses include inventing citations, replacing reading, producing final prose without understanding, or treating confident output as verified fact.</p>\n<p>For Assignment 1, the strongest AI workflow is bounded: ask for help generating questions or comparison criteria, verify every factual claim from independent sources, write the reasoning yourself, and declare the interaction. That keeps AI in the support-tool role.</p>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Engineering Practice Maps</h2>\n<div class=\"diagram\"><strong>Process flow</strong><div class=\"flow\"><span>Set assignment question</span><span>Find credible sources</span><span>Use AI only for bounded support</span><span>Verify claims</span><span>Compare options</span><span>Write human reasoning</span><span>Declare tool use</span></div></div>\n<div class=\"table-wrap\"><table><thead><tr><th>AI use</th><th>Engineering value</th><th>Risk control</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Brainstorming options</td><td>Expands the option set before evaluation</td><td>Screen ideas against constraints and sources</td></tr><tr><td>Summarising sources</td><td>Saves time on first pass</td><td>Read the original before citing</td></tr><tr><td>Draft critique</td><td>Finds missing structure or clarity</td><td>Do not let AI invent content or grade itself</td></tr><tr><td>Data analysis/literature scanning</td><td>Can detect patterns in large sets</td><td>Use human checks and domain expertise</td></tr><tr><td>Final report prose</td><td>Can improve language</td><td>Keep authorship, evidence, and judgement transparent</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<div class=\"table-wrap\"><table><thead><tr><th>Source check</th><th>Question to ask</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Currency</td><td>Is the information recent enough for this engineering context?</td></tr><tr><td>Authority</td><td>Who wrote it, and why should they be trusted?</td></tr><tr><td>Purpose</td><td>Is it informing, selling, persuading, or simplifying?</td></tr><tr><td>Evidence</td><td>Can the claim be traced to data, standards, or credible research?</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Key Terms</h2>\n<div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Generative AI</strong>A tool that produces text, images, code, or other outputs from patterns in training data and prompts.</div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Hallucination</strong>A plausible-sounding but false or unsupported AI output.</div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>APA referencing</strong>A citation style used to show where information came from and let readers trace evidence.</div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>CRAAP test</strong>A source-evaluation checklist for currency, relevance/reliability, authority, accuracy/equity, and purpose.</div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Disclosure</strong>A clear statement of whether and how AI or another support tool was used.</div></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Practical Takeaways</h2>\n<ul><li>Never cite an AI answer as evidence; find the source it should have come from.</li><li>Use AI for questions, outlines, critique, or accessibility, then verify and write the engineering judgement yourself.</li><li>For every source in a report, be able to explain why it is credible enough to affect the decision.</li></ul>\n</section>\n"
