        "subtitle": "This lecture teaches the difference between hazards, risks, probability, and consequence. It shows that engineers reduce harm by identifying the true hazard, then eliminating it, lowering the probability of release, or reducing the consequence if release occurs.",
        "contentHtml": "\n<section>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>This lecture teaches the difference between hazards, risks, probability, and consequence. It shows that engineers reduce harm by identifying the true hazard, then eliminating it, lowering the probability of release, or reducing the consequence if release occurs.</p>\n<div class=\"callout\"><strong>Capture note.</strong> This static page was written from this folder&#x27;s transcript and metadata. Capture: Alternate capture; media id 4fd60987-126b-49d9-98a8-4592c474542a; transcript segments 1115; approx. transcript words 7644.</div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2>\n<ul><li>Define hazard, risk, probability, and consequence in engineering safety language.</li><li>Avoid confusing a hazard with an accident or consequence.</li><li>Use examples such as vehicles, solvents, bridges, and engineering failures to classify risks.</li><li>Select controls that eliminate hazards, reduce probability, or reduce consequence.</li></ul>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Detailed Study Notes</h2>\n<h3>Course connections before risk</h3>\n<p>The lecture begins by locating risk inside the wider ENGR101 map: engineering process, AI, problem solving, EWB, ethics, sustainability, and teamwork. Risk is not a separate topic; it applies to every step of design. A solution can look elegant and still fail if hazards are poorly identified.</p>\n<p>The lecturer also signals professional reality. Large engineering problems are often large because they carry serious safety, environmental, economic, or social consequences. Engineers therefore need vocabulary that separates what can cause harm from how likely and how severe that harm might be.</p>\n<h3>Hazard is the source of possible harm</h3>\n<p>A hazard is the physical situation or stored energy with potential to damage people, equipment, or environment. The lecture uses examples such as pressure, heat, momentum, toxicity, electricity, kinetic energy, and flammable materials. A hazard exists even when it is controlled; the point is that it could escape in the wrong direction or at the wrong time.</p>\n<p>The hardest study skill is not memorising the definition but applying it. Getting hit by a car is not the hazard; pedestrians and traffic interacting, or the uncontrolled kinetic energy of a vehicle, is the hazard. A broken leg is not the hazard either; it is a consequence.</p>\n<h3>Risk combines hazard, probability, and consequence</h3>\n<p>Risk is described as the likelihood of a hazard occurring and how bad the result will be. The useful mental equation is: risk equals hazard presence times probability times consequence. Hazard is binary: if the hazard is removed, that specific risk becomes zero. Probability and consequence are then estimated or controlled.</p>\n<p>The vehicle example makes this quantitative. A heavy vehicle at highway speed carries kinetic energy. Lowering speed reduces both the probability of a crash, because the driver has more time to react, and the consequence, because kinetic energy scales with speed squared. An airbag, by contrast, does not stop the crash from occurring but reduces injury consequences for occupants.</p>\n<h3>Failure cases show why safety is systemic</h3>\n<p>The lecture lists well-known failures involving cladding, material failure, software, dams, and aircraft systems. These are not included as trivia. They show that failures can come from material choice, software design, sensor assumptions, training, maintenance, organisational pressure, or poor safety culture.</p>\n<p>Corporate safety culture is presented as something students will see in industry. The point is broader than slogans: every task should be performed with concern for safety, and that mindset should follow engineers home as well as into laboratories, factories, roads, and sites.</p>\n<h3>Control strategies</h3>\n<p>The strongest control is hazard elimination: if a flammable solvent is replaced with a genuinely non-flammable one, the flammability hazard is removed. But substitution may introduce new hazards such as toxicity or environmental harm, so the engineer must re-run the risk analysis rather than declare victory.</p>\n<p>If a hazard cannot be eliminated, reduce probability through procedures, maintenance, better design, training, sensors, or equipment. Reduce consequence through airbags, containment, guardrails, emergency response, or separation distances. The bridge example shows that the same fall probability can have radically different consequences depending on what lies below.</p>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Engineering Practice Maps</h2>\n<div class=\"diagram\"><strong>Process flow</strong><div class=\"flow\"><span>Identify true hazard</span><span>Estimate probability</span><span>Estimate consequence</span><span>Eliminate if possible</span><span>Reduce probability</span><span>Reduce consequence</span><span>Review new hazards</span></div></div>\n<div class=\"table-wrap\"><table><thead><tr><th>Example</th><th>Hazard</th><th>Probability controls</th><th>Consequence controls</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Vehicle at highway speed</td><td>Uncontrolled kinetic energy transfer</td><td>Speed limits, driver training, road design, ABS, maintenance</td><td>Seatbelts, airbags, crumple zones, barriers</td></tr><tr><td>Flammable solvent transport</td><td>Flammable chemical energy and toxicity</td><td>Handling procedures, sealed containers, route planning</td><td>Secondary containment, fire suppression, spill response</td></tr><tr><td>Bridge crossing</td><td>Potential energy from height</td><td>Guardrails, surface maintenance, access controls</td><td>Fall arrest, rescue access, safer landing environment</td></tr><tr><td>Software-controlled machine</td><td>Incorrect control action or missing interlock</td><td>Testing, redundancy, requirements review</td><td>Dose limits, shutdown systems, operator training</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Key Terms</h2>\n<div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Hazard</strong>A condition or source of energy with potential to cause harm if control is lost.</div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Risk</strong>The combination of a hazard, the probability of it escaping control, and the consequence if it does.</div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Consequence</strong>The severity of harm: injury, death, cost, environmental damage, legal impact, or system loss.</div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Probability</strong>How often or how likely the hazard is to produce the unwanted event.</div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Safety culture</strong>Shared expectations and behaviours that make safety part of every task rather than an afterthought.</div></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Practical Takeaways</h2>\n<ul><li>When doing a risk table, do not write the injury as the hazard; ask what source of energy or exposure causes it.</li><li>Separate controls by what they change: hazard, probability, or consequence.</li><li>After substituting a material or method, check whether a new hazard has been introduced.</li></ul>\n</section>\n"
