        "slug": "2026-05-27_ENGR101-26S1-LecB-Foundations-of-Engineering",
        "date": "2026-05-27",
        "title": "Final Exam Preparation and Applied Ethics Practice",
        "subtitle": "The final live lecture prepares students for the ENGR101 exam. It covers logistics, pass rules, drawing-question expectations, special consideration and reset exams, time management, and a worked ethics-style question about changing test data.",
        "contentHtml": "\n<section>\n<h2>Overview</h2>\n<p>The final live lecture prepares students for the ENGR101 exam. It covers logistics, pass rules, drawing-question expectations, special consideration and reset exams, time management, and a worked ethics-style question about changing test data.</p>\n<div class=\"callout\"><strong>Capture note.</strong> This static page was written from this folder&#x27;s transcript and metadata. Capture: Lecture capture; media id cd38fc70-5491-485e-9d80-8e84c334e1db; transcript segments 561; approx. transcript words 6879.</div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Learning Objectives</h2>\n<ul><li>Describe the exam structure, logistics, and pass requirements.</li><li>Prepare for the drawing question with correct materials and freehand expectations.</li><li>Use marks-to-time tactics across a long exam.</li><li>Apply ethical frameworks, stakeholder analysis, and professional codes to a case question.</li></ul>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Detailed Study Notes</h2>\n<h3>Exam logistics and mindset</h3>\n<p>The lecturer frames the exam as students&#x27; first university exam experience and reminds them that they are close to finishing a significant first-year milestone. The exam is three hours long and covers material from across the semester through case studies and applied questions.</p>\n<p>Students will receive an examination identification number separate from their student number. They need to know what to bring, where to put names and IDs, and how the drawing booklet or drawing block works. These are simple details, but simple details become stressful if first seen under exam conditions.</p>\n<h3>Drawing question rules</h3>\n<p>There will be a drawing question. Students should bring a pencil and eraser. A ruler may be used to measure where required, but not to create the freehand drawing lines; the point is to show sketching skill rather than instrument drafting. Drawing work goes in the drawing block, while other questions go in the answer booklet.</p>\n<p>This connects directly back to the sketching lectures: construction lines, orthographic views, labels, and clear freehand technique matter. Practise drawing under time pressure before the exam.</p>\n<h3>Pass rules, special consideration, and reset</h3>\n<p>The course requires more than 40 percent in the exam and 50 percent overall. Most students do well enough on assignments that the exam hurdle is the main risk. A special consideration exam is scheduled for 30 June for justified inability to attend the main exam, and students must alert the course as soon as they know they cannot attend.</p>\n<p>The reset exam is different from special consideration and has criteria: students must have submitted all assignments and met the stated assignment-average expectations. It is not a strategy for improving a mark; it is a recovery pathway for students who otherwise meet the course conditions but fail the exam hurdle.</p>\n<h3>Time management by marks</h3>\n<p>The lecture uses a past 2024 exam as an example while noting that the 2026 exam is longer. The tactic is to map marks to minutes, leave reading/checking time, and avoid letting one question steal time from the rest of the paper.</p>\n<p>For a 100-mark, 180-minute exam, students should still be disciplined. A 15-mark question should not consume half an hour unless the rest of the paper is already secure. Write enough to answer the prompt, then move on.</p>\n<h3>Ethics worked example: changing test data</h3>\n<p>The worked ethics question asks whether it is ethical to change test data so a solution appears to meet contract requirements. The class identifies stakeholders, then applies ethical frameworks. From a consequence view, stakeholders include clients, users, the public, employer, engineer, and anyone harmed by false compliance. From a virtue view, honesty and integrity argue against changing data.</p>\n<p>The Engineering New Zealand code is used as an applied guide. The answer should not just say &#x27;the code says no&#x27;; it should connect the code to public safety, truthful communication, competence, and avoiding harm to people or environment. The obvious conclusion is that falsifying or manipulating data is not ethical.</p>\n<h3>Case-study thinking</h3>\n<p>Later exam discussion moves into case-study material involving partnership, participation, protection, and examples tied to the facts of the prompt. The marking emphasis is on connection: examples must be tied back to the case study rather than listed generically.</p>\n<p>This is the best final study advice for the whole course. ENGR101 questions rarely ask for isolated definitions only. They ask you to use definitions, frameworks, and tools on a realistic scenario.</p>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Engineering Practice Maps</h2>\n<div class=\"diagram\"><strong>Process flow</strong><div class=\"flow\"><span>Read case</span><span>Identify stakeholders</span><span>Name relevant framework</span><span>Apply to facts</span><span>Use code or course tool</span><span>State justified conclusion</span><span>Check time and move on</span></div></div>\n<div class=\"table-wrap\"><table><thead><tr><th>Exam area</th><th>What to prepare</th><th>Common risk</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Logistics</td><td>Exam ID, location, materials, booklet rules</td><td>Wasting time or panicking over avoidable admin</td></tr><tr><td>Drawing</td><td>Freehand orthographic/isometric practice, pencil and eraser</td><td>Using instruments where freehand is expected</td></tr><tr><td>Ethics</td><td>Three frameworks, stakeholders, Engineering NZ code</td><td>Defining theories without applying them</td></tr><tr><td>Risk/process/sustainability</td><td>Case-based use of tools and concepts</td><td>Writing generic course slogans</td></tr><tr><td>Time</td><td>Marks-to-minutes plan</td><td>Overwriting the first question</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n<div class=\"table-wrap\"><table><thead><tr><th>Ethics lens for data manipulation</th><th>Likely reasoning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Rules/duty</td><td>Changing data breaches honesty, contract truthfulness, and professional duties.</td></tr><tr><td>Consequences</td><td>False compliance can harm users, public trust, client decisions, and the engineer&#x27;s employer.</td></tr><tr><td>Virtue</td><td>Integrity and honesty require reporting the mismatch rather than hiding it.</td></tr><tr><td>Professional code</td><td>Protect public safety, communicate truthfully, and avoid misleading conduct.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Key Terms</h2>\n<div class=\"term-grid\"><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Exam hurdle</strong>A minimum exam mark that must be achieved independently of the overall course mark.</div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Special consideration</strong>An exam pathway for justified inability to attend or complete the scheduled exam.</div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Reset exam</strong>A separate recovery exam available only under stated course criteria.</div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Stakeholder analysis</strong>Identifying who is affected by an ethical or engineering decision.</div><div class=\"term-card\"><strong>Marks-to-time planning</strong>Allocating exam time in proportion to marks so no question consumes unfair time.</div></div>\n</section>\n<section><h2>Practical Takeaways</h2>\n<ul><li>Practise at least one ethics question by applying all three frameworks to one scenario.</li><li>For drawing, practise freehand construction under a timer rather than only reviewing notes.</li><li>In every case-study answer, tie examples back to the facts given in the question.</li></ul>\n</section>\n"
